[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6 {Welcome to this course! This course features interesting antidotes to most of White's sidelines against the Caro-Kann. As White is struggling to find anything substantial in the two mainlines against the Caro (the Advance,2.d4d53.e5, and the Classical3.Nc3or3.Nd2), more and more players, following the lead of top grandmasters, have turned to various sidelines to try to dig for an advantage, or at least get interesting positions where they can play for a win. If you're a Caro Kann player and want an extra weapon or two against those sidelines, this course is for you.The idea for this course started back in 2021, as during lockdown times I would occasionally play a training game against a colleague at Chessable, or participate in a Chessable staff blitz tournament, and I was frustrated by my colleagues' use of annoying sidelines against my Caro-Kann. I set out to refute the analysis of Chessforlife in his Chessable course Beat the Caro-Kann, as a few of them were using his ideas, and also wanted something new against the Accelerated Panov. My analysis of those lines eventually involved into the larger project of this course, and you can find my ideas against the Two Knights and the Accelerated Panov in the first two chapters.I then won a game in the Dutch team league using my own preparation, and from there, I thought 'Why not look into some other funky sidelines as well?' And eventually this led to the creation of the other six (and a half) chapters.A word about style and correctness. I am a firm believer of the idea that chess is a concrete game. General principles matter in chess, in the opening too, but in the end an idea or a variation works or doesn't work, and this is often based on (what are at first) minor details. You can see this, for instance, in the chapter on the Exchange variation where I analyze the crazy looking7...e5!?- it leaves two pawns hanging, but in the end the details work well (enough) for Black. Or consider the line1.e4c62.c4d53.exd5cxd54.cxd5Nf65.Qa4+Bd76.Qb3e6- in some lines Black should retake the pawn on d5 with the knight and in other lines he should retake with the e6-pawn, and whether one or the other is correct will depend on small, concrete details.My focus has been on catching White by surprise. Many white players use sidelines against the Caro because they want to get a comfortable game without having to learn a huge amount of theory. By taking them by surprise early, we get them out of that comfort zone and force them to find their way on what is rightfully our opening turf.Some of the lines advocated here are, if White plays correctly, quite drawish (e.g. chapter one). Others lead to very complicated play (e.g. chapter two). I have tried to only recommend variations that are objectively correct, but in a few cases Black does not equalize fully and I will point out when that happens. I think all of these lines are at least playable, though. In the end, my idea with this course is that the variations recommended here supplement a player's Caro-Kann repertoire, so that they can vary their lines if they want to. But, it is up to you what you want to do with it.Happy hunting with the Caro!} 
*
