[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Chess is a Concrete Game"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {I would like to show an example from a mainstream, topical variation that exemplifies that much of opening theory ultimately depends on concrete ideas. I'll be borrowing a bit of analysis from GM Surya Ganguly's LTR on the Nimzo/Semi-Tarrasch(one of my favorite repertoires on our website, by the way), as I found some of his comments remarkable.} 1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. dxc4
5. Bg2
5. c5
6. O-O
6. Nc6
7. dxc5 {This is a very trendy line for both colors. Black's setup against the Catalan with 4...dxc4, 5...c5 and 6...Nc6 is explored in both GM Surya Ganguly's Nimzo/Semi-Tarrasch LTR, and IM Christof Sielecki's Keep It Simple for Black. Meanwhile, the 7. dxc5 endgame variation is recommended in both GM Srinath Narayanan's Catalan LTR and FM Kamil Plichta's King's Indian Attack LTR.} 
7. Qxd1
8. Rxd1
8. Bxc5
9. Nbd2
9. c3
10. bxc3
10. O-O
11. Nb3
11. Be7
12. Nfd4
12. Nxd4
13. cxd4
13. Nd5 {Up until here we're following one of the mainlines after 7. dxc5. Play centers around the question whether Black can complete his development and nullify White's pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal.} 
14. Na5 {A minor alternative to the mainline that continues14.Bd2f5.} 
14. Bb4
15. Nc4
15. Bd7
16. Rb1 {This seems difficult to handle for Black, but there is a concrete solution.} 
16. Nc3
17. Bd2 {It turns out White isn't really sacrificing an exchange, as after either rook capture White would answer Bxb4 and Black's knight remains trapped and would soon be lost.However, Black can (and should) grab the e2-pawn, as this capture comes with check.} 
17. Nxe2+ {Now GM Ganguly gives two lines, one with18.Kf1and one with18.Kh1. His comment about18.Kh1,which stood out to me, is: 'Counterintuitive, but it has a point. As bizarre as it seems, the Kh1 move is against any back rank threats :).'I'll get back to 18. Kh1 in a moment, but let's first consider the other king move.} 
18. Kf1
18. Bxd2
19. Rxb7
19. Nc3
20. Rxd2
20. Rab8 {and this is the mentioned back rank threat: White can't capture21.Rxd7?or21.Rxa7?due to21...Rb1+and mate. Thus Black manages to keep equality in this way.Meanwhile, the18.Kh1line hinges on another important tactical detail:18...Bxd219.Rxd2Rac8and now after20.Nd6Black wins a crucial tempo with20...Rc6!,attacking the knight on d6, as21.Bxc6Bxc6+comes with check - all because the king is on h1!By the way, the move16.Rb1!?has only been seen twice so far, both in strong Grandmaster games with classical time controls, and in both cases Black did not dare to venture16...Nc3!.White won both games. Perhaps objectively the line with 14. Na5 through 16. Rb1 is not the most testing, but it sets Black concrete problems, and if they are not aware that there is an equally concrete solution, it can be near impossible to figure out over the board.} 
