1. e4
1. c6 {Please note that this is NOT a full Caro-Kann repertoire. Instead this is an assortment of interesting/playable sidelines for Black against various of White's tries against the Caro-Kann.Here's an overview of what you'd have to study yourself. I don't believe any lines for White that I've omitted are particularly troublesome, but I would still advise you to know what to do against them:A) Most importantly, I don't cover sidelines in the Advance variation2.d4d53.e5Bf5. Here, some lines that I skip over are4.c4,4.g4,4.Nd2,4.c3,4.Be3and4.Ne2. In the line4.h4h5I skip over White's alternatives to5.Bd3, and in the line4.Nf3e65.Be2c5I omit White's alternatives to the mainline6.Be3Qb67.Nc3Nc68.O-O.B) My chapter on the Classical variation2.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Bf5skips over sidelines such as5.Nc5and5.Ng3Bg66.Bc4,6.Nh3,6.N1e2and after the main move6.h4h6I skip similar lines with7.Nh3,7.N1e2or7.Bc4or a combination of these moves.C) My recommendation against the Panov is2.d4d53.exd5cxd54.c4and now4...e6!?followed by ...Bb4 and ...Ne7. However, be aware that in case of an Accelerated Panov (1. e4 c6 2. c4) you could get move-ordered out of this possibility, so you can't rely on this variation against the Panov 100% of the time.D) The Accelerated Panov2.c4d53.exd5cxd54.cxd5Nf6: here the main tries are 5. Bb5+ and 5. Qa4+, which I both cover. But there are also some independent lines with5.Nc3Nxd5, such as6.Bc4or6.Nf3Nc67.Bb5which I don't cover.E) The Two Knights variation2.Nf3d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Nf6and now the main continuation is 5. Qe2 which is covered. However, in this position White can also play5.Nxf6+exf66.d4and transpose to the classical 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 (albeit a harmless variation), which I don't cover.F) Finally, there are several minor sidelines on move 2 which I don't cover, including but not limited to the following:2.b3,2.Nc3d53.Qf3,2.f4and2.Bc4.} 
