[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nc3 {(Or2.Nf3d53.Nc3)} 
2. d5
3. Nf3 {This is the starting position of the Two Knights variation, one of those lines which has become increasingly popular as White's attempts to get any advantage against the Caro-Kann in the mainlines, ie. the Advance variation or the Classical, have been frustrated.} 
3. dxe4 {3...Bg4is the mainline but3...dxe4is also played quite often.} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {A straightforward way to continue. White's main move is now5.Qe2.} 
5. Qe2 {5.Nxf6+is a popular alternative, but5...exf66.d4would transpose to the Classical line2.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6+exf6where White has played the non-critical6.Nf3.Hence 5. Qe2 is the main independent try for White here.} 
5. Na6 {This rare move is my suggestion. The normal continuation5...Nxe46.Qxe4and now6...Nd7should equalize for Black as well, but with 5... Na6 we can attempt to catch White off guard.Now the main recommendation in a few Chessable courses is 6. d4.} 
6. d4 {6.Nxf6+gxf6is also often tried by White and needs to be checked. However, this seems to me to be a version of the ...gxf6 Caro-Kann which is worse for White than usual, as the queen is not so well placed on e2 here. In fact, White needs to watch out for various tactics involving ...Nb4, which we'll explore.} 
 {After 6.d4, for some reason, the top games have continued6...Qd5?!7.Nc3!Qa5when I think Black enters a poor man's Scandinavian. Meanwhile there is a very clean (albeit dry) equalizer for Black:} 6. Nxe4
7. Qxe4
7. Qd5 {White cannot really avoid the exchange of queens, again because of ...Nb4 ideas, while} 
8. Qxd5
8. cxd5 {is a comfortable ending for Black, albeit a bit drawish. Still, I'd consider that a success for Black, as it's White who should be able to show something out of the opening.} 
