[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 5...Na6!? Or How To Make The Two Knights Harmless"]
[Black "Two Knights 5... Na6!? - 6. Nxf6+ with 7. g3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Nf3 {The two knights variation is quite popular among players who look for an interesting sideline against the Caro-Kann. Along with the exchange variation it's probably the sideline I've faced the most.} 
3. dxe4 {3...Bg4is the main line and sees Black giving up the bishop pair in exchange for a very solid position. It's discussed extensively in Erwin L'Ami's course.} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {A straightforward way to continue. White's main move is now5.Qe2.} 
5. Qe2 {The most popular and also the computer's favorite choice. White prevents ...Nbd7, as5...Nbd7??6.Nd6#is mate, and otherwise it remains difficult for Black to develop the c8-bishop.5.Nxf6+exf6usually transposes to the Classical with 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6, but with White's knight prematurely developed to f3, which means this is not a critical variation. The Classical Caro-Kann with 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 is discussed extensively in both L'Ami's LTR and Sielecki's Keep it Simple for Black, and I have nothing to add to their lines.5.Ng3is also an insipid reply, as Black can comfortably develop as follows:5...h56.h4Otherwise the g3-knight will be pushed away again.6...Bg4followed by ...e6, ...Bd6 etc. Black is already on the better side of equality.} 
5. Na6 {This is a rare continuation, but it has been seen recently in some high-level games. We ask White how exactly he intends to develop next as the e2-queen blocks the bishop on f1, introduce ideas of ... Nb4 when the queen will be misplaced on e2, and also introduce the idea of exchanging on e4 followed by ...Qd5.The immediate5...Nxe46.Qxe4Qd5is less good as White can sidestep with7.Qh4and then try to exploit Black's centralized queen. It doesn't seem to fully equalize for Black. However, there is nothing wrong with5...Nxe46.Qxe4Nd7followed by ...Nf6, but that's probably what White is expecting.} 
6. Nxf6+ {This is White's most significant alternative to6.d4,and has been featured in quite a few games. However, the resulting positions are actually very trappy for White! The resource ...Nb4 is often available, exploiting the (mis) positioning of White's queen on e2.In case of6.c3I suggest6...Qd5when White should probably play7.Nxf6+gxf6transposing to 6. Nxf6+ gxf6 7. c3 Qd5, as7.d3Bf5is quite comfortable for Black.} 
6. gxf6
7. g3 {This already brings White into trouble.} 
7. Nb4
8. d3
8. Qd5 {Threatening ...Nxc2+.} 
9. Bg2
9. Bg4 {White has to play the very awkward10.Kd1just to avoid losing material.} 
