6. Nxf6+ {This is White's most significant alternative to6.d4,and has been featured in quite a few games. However, the resulting positions are actually very trappy for White! The resource ...Nb4 is often available, exploiting the (mis) positioning of White's queen on e2.In case of6.c3I suggest6...Qd5when White should probably play7.Nxf6+gxf6transposing to 6. Nxf6+ gxf6 7. c3 Qd5, as7.d3Bf5is quite comfortable for Black.} 
6. gxf6
7. d4 {Grabbing central space is the most straightforward option for White.} 
7. h5 {I think this is both a good move and also a practical one. White needs to use several moves to sort out his kingside, but at the same time he now has to deal with the idea of our h-pawn advancing, eventually, to h3. If Black could get the pawn on h3, force White to play g2-g3, then a setup with ...Qd5 and ...Bg4 would become very powerful.} 
8. g3 {Probably the last possible opportunity White has to play this move. It should be noted that against the line1.e4c62.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6+gxf6,developing the bishop to g2 is considered to be the mayor antidote which gives White some advantage. White players who know this might be tempted to play in similar fashion here.} 
8. h4 {I think we should make use of the opportunity to get rid of our h-pawn. However, Stockfish gives a decent alternative in the forcing line8...Bg49.h3Bxf310.Qxf3Nb411.Qb3(only move)11...Qd5!12.Qxd5(only move again)12...cxd5and the endgame should be manageable for Black. This endgame is not everyone's cup of tea, though.} 
9. Nxh4 {9.gxh4?can't be right. White won't hold on to the pawn in the long run and wrecks his own structure for no reason.} 
9. Qxd4
10. Bg2 {After10.Nf3,10...Qa4!intending ...Bf5 and ...Nb4 piling up on the c2-pawn is surprisingly strong.} 
10. Bg4
11. Nf3
11. Qd7 {Followed by ...e5 and, if allowed, castling long. I don't think Black has anything to fear as we have a firm grip on the kingside - it's not clear how White is going to dislodge the g4-bishop.} 
