7. d4 {Grabbing central space is the most straightforward option for White.} 
7. h5 {I think this is both a good move and also a practical one. White needs to use several moves to sort out his kingside, but at the same time he now has to deal with the idea of our h-pawn advancing, eventually, to h3. If Black could get the pawn on h3, force White to play g2-g3, then a setup with ...Qd5 and ...Bg4 would become very powerful.} 
8. Be3
8. h4
9. h3 {White should probably prevent ...h3.} 
9. Nb4 {Rerouting the knight to d5 while also creating a small trap.} 
10. a3 {10.c4??Bf5!is a recurring motif in such positions.10.Qd2is a decent move, but after10...Nd5Black is at least getting the bishop pair and can't be worse.} 
10. Nd5 {10...Qa5is possible, but after11.c3the knight would have to move to go to d5 anyway.} 
11. Bd2
11. Qd6 {Intending to put the knight on f4 after White kicks it away with c2-c4.} 
12. c4
12. Nf4 {White usually has some advantage based on the better pawn structure in these ...gxf6 Caro-Kann positions, but here the kingside has been fixed in Black's favor and the knight is very strongly posted on f4, which means the position is at least equal.13.Bxf4?Qxf4is already a bit better for Black, who can activate the bishops with ...Bh6 and ...Bf5.13.Qe4is called for, when13...Qe6invites an unbalanced endgame with14.Qxe6Nxe6.the knight is great on e6, but the c8-bishop is bit blocked in. Black can usually continue with the moves ...Bd7, ...O-O-O, ...Bh6 and ...Rdg8. ...Rh5 is sometimes also a nice option to have, while ...Bg7 and ...f5 is another way of activating the dark-squared bishop.} 
