7. dxe4 {Probably White's best try in this position, but it's not very obvious at first.} 
7. e5 {This pawn is indirectly protected -8.Nxe5??Qa5+.} 
8. Qd2 {The only move that's a bit testing. Suddenly there's a combination of threats of Bxa6, Nxe5 and Qxd8+, all somewhat unpleasant moves to face.If White keeps the queens on the board with something like8.Bd2, then8...Qc7followed by moves like ...f6, ...Be6, ...Nc5 in no particular order is very pleasant for Black.} 
8. Qxd2+ {We don't have much choice here.} 
9. Bxd2
9. Nc5 {Again not much choice. Otherwise it's not possible to defend against both Bxa6 ruining our pawn structure and Nxe5 winning a pawn.} 
10. Nxe5 {Other moves would allow ...f6. White needs to make something of the lead in development immediately.} 
10. Nxe4
11. Bc4
11. Nd6 {Next we kick back the e5-knight with ...f6, then develop with ...Bd7 and ...O-O-O. The position is pretty equal. Unfortunately it's very dry with an equal pawn structure, but sometimes that can't be avoided as Black.} 
