1. e4
1. c6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Nf3 {The two knights variation is quite popular among players who look for an interesting sideline against the Caro-Kann. Along with the exchange variation it's probably the sideline I've faced the most.} 
3. dxe4 {3...Bg4is the main line and sees Black giving up the bishop pair in exchange for a very solid position. It's discussed extensively in Erwin L'Ami's course.} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {A straightforward way to continue. White's main move is now5.Qe2.} 
5. Qe2 {The most popular and also the computer's favorite choice. White prevents ...Nbd7, as5...Nbd7??6.Nd6#is mate, and otherwise it remains difficult for Black to develop the c8-bishop.5.Nxf6+exf6usually transposes to the Classical with 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6, but with White's knight prematurely developed to f3, which means this is not a critical variation. The Classical Caro-Kann with 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 is discussed extensively in both L'Ami's LTR and Sielecki's Keep it Simple for Black, and I have nothing to add to their lines.5.Ng3is also an insipid reply, as Black can comfortably develop as follows:5...h56.h4Otherwise the g3-knight will be pushed away again.6...Bg4followed by ...e6, ...Bd6 etc. Black is already on the better side of equality.} 
5. Na6 {This is a rare continuation, but it has been seen recently in some high-level games. We ask White how exactly he intends to develop next as the e2-queen blocks the bishop on f1, introduce ideas of ... Nb4 when the queen will be misplaced on e2, and also introduce the idea of exchanging on e4 followed by ...Qd5.The immediate5...Nxe46.Qxe4Qd5is less good as White can sidestep with7.Qh4and then try to exploit Black's centralized queen. It doesn't seem to fully equalize for Black. However, there is nothing wrong with5...Nxe46.Qxe4Nd7followed by ...Nf6, but that's probably what White is expecting.} 
6. d4 {Chessforlife's recommendation, but he doesn't consider the following response.} 
6. Nxe4 {Apparently this is a novelty. It seems the most logical move to me, though. Practically all games instead continued6...Qd5, when after7.Nc3!Qa5Black enters an inferior type of Scandinavian position.My intention is to first exchange knights with6...Nxe4and only after7.Qxe4play7...Qd5!, when White can't really escape the exchange of queens and the game heads into a dry, equalish endgame.} 
7. Qxe4 {In his LTR 1. e4. Adhiban considers this position slightly better for White because of the free development, but after 7... Qd5 the endgame just seems equal to me.} 
7. Qd5 {This way we force a typical Caro-Kann endgame, as White's attempts to avoid the queen exchange mostly run into ...Nb4 here.} 
8. Qxd5
8. cxd5 {Initially Stockfish is not a fan of Black's position, but this opinion is tempered the deeper the computer's analysis goes. White has some initiative and a slight edge in development, but there is nothing concrete and Black has no weaknesses. The knight on a6 is often a bit misplaced, but it can easily be rerouted. White also has a tactical idea with Ne5 and Bb5+, but it is easily parried and after that White's pieces can be chased back.In sum, I think this endgame is equal and the better player will prevail. It's not something to worry about for Black, plus we get to enjoy our favorite Carlsbad pawn structure.} 
9. Bxa6 {This is what my Chessable colleague and fellow author WFM Maaike Keetman played against me when faced with this variation. Even though White is not necessarily worse after this, I do think it goes against the nature of the position. Black's doubled a-pawns won't be a weakness and Black's bishop pair, especially the uncontested light-squared bishop, should guarantee him comfortable play.} 
9. bxa6
10. b3 {The only white plan that makes sense to me. After other moves Black should still play similarly: ...Bf5, ...e6 and ...Be7, perhaps also ... f6 and ...Kf7 and move the rooks over to the queenside.} 
10. Bf5
11. c4 {White's idea - he creates a passed pawn on the c-file. Still I don't think Black has anything to worry.} 
11. dxc4
12. bxc4
12. e6 {Note that the f5-bishop provides nice control over the b1-square, which means White's rook are hard to activate. Next Black can start to target the c4- and d4-pawns.} 
