*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Accelerated Panov With a Rook Sac"]
[Black "Chapter 2 Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {This chapter is dedicated to my colleague FM Tobias Kabos, who fueled my irrational hatred for the 2. c4 line by beating me with it at a Chessable blitz tournament. To my hilarity(sorry Tobias!), I saw that in a recent bullet game on Lichess someone played 5... Bd7 6. Qb3 e6!(my suggestion in this chapter)against him, after which he lost in a handful of moves because his queen got trapped!} 1. e4
1. c6
2. c4
2. d5
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6
5. Qa4+ {5.Nc3As mentioned in the introduction, there are some independent lines for White with this move as well which I'm not going to analyze, so for a full repertoire you have to do some work yourself. And of course White can at this moment transpose to a regular Panov by playing5.d4.5.Bb5+Apart from 5. Qa4+ I analyze this move as well. Against both 5. Qa4+ and 5. Bb5+ the main way for Black to reply is 5... Nbd7, but against 5. Bb5+ interposing the bishop has also been played occasionally.5...Bd76.Bc4The only critical move, hanging on to d5 for now, but we can gain some queenside space attacking White's bishop.6...b57.Bb3a58.a38. a4 is also a move here.8...a4This doesn't look that great unless you know Black's next move.9.Ba2b4!An important novelty. White undoubtedly will take on b4 now or after moving the bishop out to c4 again, after which we can continue ...Na6xb4 with interesting play.I don't think this line fully equalizes for Black  (the main line sees White retain an extra pawn albeit Black has decent compensation), but it was interesting enough to analyze it in some detail and present it to you. After all, you can decide for yourself whether to incorporate it in your repertoire or not.} 
 {After5.Qa4+the move5...Nbd7is, of course, the main try and there is nothing wrong with it. However, I always seem to go wrong somewhere in the resulting middlegames, and White often knows quite well what to do and what to expect from Black. So my thought process: why not get White out of their comfort zone much earlier?} 5. Bd7 {This is often seen as a bit dubious because after} 
6. Qb3 {as Christof Sielecki put it in Keep it Simple for Black, Black isn't getting the d5-pawn back easily. This is true! However, after 6... e6! Black gets great play for the sacrificed material.} 
6. e6 {Practically a novelty (when I created this chapter at the start of 2022 there were only four games with this move in my database, and in only one of them did Black correctly follow up this idea), offering pawns on e6, b7 and the a8-rook as well. This is a really fun line as it is very trappy for White, who will no doubt be on their own after this move! This fact cannot be overstated - White will not be expecting the move 6... e6, as Black's main replies here have been 6... Qc7, 6... Qb6 and 6... Na6, all of which are just not good enough.After 6... e6 at worst Black will get an endgame a pawn down but with full compensation - the move equalizes, and if White goes wrong (which is highly likely) he'll be worse or losing.} 
7. dxe6 {Some alternatives:A)7.Nc3Nxd58.Nf3If White refuses to grab any material, Black will get a very comfortable position as the queen on b3 is misplaced in this IQP structure.8...Bd69.g3Bc610.Bg2O-O11.O-OQb6⩱We wouldn't mind trading down to an ending that's slightly better for Black.B)7.Qxb7Naturally, going for the a8-rook is one of the critical continuations which we'll analyze in detail.7...exd5!8.Qxa8White takes the rook, but in the end the queen is not surviving this adventure. The question really is how much material White will get for the queen. The main line continues as follows:8...Bc59.Qb7Bb610.a4(to play Bb5)10...O-O11.Bb5Re8+12.Ne2Rxe2+!13.Bxe2Bc6After a more or less forced line White's queen is finally trapped, though he has 2 rooks and a pawn for her majesty after14.Qxb6Qxb6. Stockfish, however, argues that Black has a clear advantage in the resulting positions, which we'll explore further. Of course, there were a lot of things happening along the way and White has various other tries after 7. Qxb7 exd5, which we'll look at in detail. A typical tactical idea is13.Kxe2Qe7+!followed by a check with the d7-bishop, leading to a discovered attack on White's queen on b7.} 
 {7. dxe6 is White's best try. This variation continues as follows:} 7. Bxe6
8. Bc4 {This is the road to equality.} 
8. Bxc4
9. Qxc4
9. Nc6
10. Nc3
10. Nb4
11. Nf3 {If White finds this line and in particular this move over the board, they are a very strong player indeed (or very well-prepared). Now Black should force the exchange of queens with} 
11. Qd3
12. Qxd3
12. Nxd3+
13. Ke2
13. O-O-O {I think this position is approximately equal. White keeps an extra pawn, for now, but Black's compensation speaks for itself.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Accelerated Panov With a Rook Sac"]
[Black "Accelerated Panov - 5. Bb5+ Bd7 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. c4 {The hallmark move of the Accelerated Panov.} 
2. d5
3. cxd5 {I would just like to point your attention to the fact that if White uses the move order3.exd5, Stockfish actually thinks the gambit3...Nf6!?4.dxc6Nxc6gives Black full compensation for the pawn. Something worth looking into.} 
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6 {Now White's main independent options are5.Qa4+and5.Bb5+, but he can also play5.Nc3(which has limited independent value) or transpose to a regular Panov with5.d4.} 
5. Bb5+ {Against this move it's also possible to play enterprisingly with 5... Bd7. However, this might be less surprising to your opponent, as here 5... Bd7 is not such a rare move (though still played 2.5 times less than 5... Nbd7).} 
5. Bd7
6. Bc4 {The only real move with which White can hope to hold on to the d5-pawn for some time. Now Black can and should make use of the placement of his bishop on d7.} 
6. b5 {We can abuse White's bishop to gain some space.} 
7. Bb3 {If at any time White plays Be2, we can just continue ...Nxd5 and enjoy the better pawn structure.} 
7. a5 {At this point7...g6is a good alternative, just finishing kingside development and only then continuing with ...a5-a4 and ...Na6-c7 etc. However, immediately pushing the queenside pawns is more fun.At this point we'll look at four possible continuations by White:8.Nf3,8.Nc3,8.a4and the main move8.a3.} 
8. Nf3
8. a4 {This way we regain the d5-pawn.} 
9. Bc2
9. b4 {The computer insists that this is the most accurate. The point is that we want to deny White the c3-square for his knight, so that after ...Nxd5 he can't challenge our central knight that way.} 
10. O-O {Note that we´ll pretty much always want to answer b3 with ...a3 and a3 with ...b3.} 
10. Nxd5
11. d4 {Probably White should continue like this. There's no need for us to fear11.Be4e612.Bxd5?!exd513.Re1+Be7.} 
11. g6 {I prefer this over ...e6 here, as11...e612.Ne5Be713.Qg4g614.Bh6is a bit annoying to deal with.Now after 11... g6 there seems to be only one concrete way in which White can pose problems for us.} 
12. Be4
12. Bc6 {12...Be613.Ng5is more awkward for us.} 
13. a3
13. b3 {This way White gets access to the c3-square at least.} 
14. Ne5
14. Bg7
15. Nxc6 {Note that after15.Qf3we can just castle short, as15...O-O16.Nxc6?Nxc617.Bxd5Nxd418.Qe4Nc2!is good for Black.} 
15. Nxc6
16. Nc3 {This is the only minor issue, we'll have to play ...e6 and allow the e-file to be opened before we can castle.} 
16. e6
17. Bxd5
17. exd5
18. Re1+
18. Kf8 {White has ruined our castling rights, but that's all really. White has pretty much no active plan here, and we can play ...h5, ...Kg8-h7 and castle artificially, after which we'll be fine.} 
