[Black "Accelerated Panov - 5. Bb5+ Bd7 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. c4 {The hallmark move of the Accelerated Panov.} 
2. d5
3. cxd5 {I would just like to point your attention to the fact that if White uses the move order3.exd5, Stockfish actually thinks the gambit3...Nf6!?4.dxc6Nxc6gives Black full compensation for the pawn. Something worth looking into.} 
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6 {Now White's main independent options are5.Qa4+and5.Bb5+, but he can also play5.Nc3(which has limited independent value) or transpose to a regular Panov with5.d4.} 
5. Bb5+ {Against this move it's also possible to play enterprisingly with 5... Bd7. However, this might be less surprising to your opponent, as here 5... Bd7 is not such a rare move (though still played 2.5 times less than 5... Nbd7).} 
5. Bd7
6. Bc4 {The only real move with which White can hope to hold on to the d5-pawn for some time. Now Black can and should make use of the placement of his bishop on d7.} 
6. b5 {We can abuse White's bishop to gain some space.} 
7. Bb3 {If at any time White plays Be2, we can just continue ...Nxd5 and enjoy the better pawn structure.} 
7. a5 {At this point7...g6is a good alternative, just finishing kingside development and only then continuing with ...a5-a4 and ...Na6-c7 etc. However, immediately pushing the queenside pawns is more fun.At this point we'll look at four possible continuations by White:8.Nf3,8.Nc3,8.a4and the main move8.a3.} 
8. Nc3
8. a4 {If we can poke White's bishop like this, we usually should do so.} 
9. Bc2
9. g6 {In this line we should develop the kingside and castle first. The reason is concrete: after9...Na610.Nf3Nb411.a3!Nbxd512.Ne5!g613.Qf3Black experiences some problems, as due to the attack on f7 there is the threat of Nxd5.The d5-pawn won't run away, and even if we develop first, the idea of ...Na6-b4xd5 will remain.Also one point about ...b4: currently we can't advance the b-pawn to b4, as that would leave our a4-pawn hanging. However, should White at some point play Qe2 or Bd3 to target the pawn on b5, then suddenly we can play ...b4, as the a4-pawn no longer hangs.} 
10. Nf3
10. Bg7
11. O-O
11. O-O {Now we're ready to continue with ...Na6-b4xd5.} 
12. d4 {If White plays12.a3Na6and then targets the b5-pawn with13.Qe2Nc714.d4, we can play14...Bg4!and exchange on f3 before regaining the d5-pawn.} 
12. Na6
13. Ne5 {Again13.a3Nc7is nothing for White.} 
13. Nb4 {Next the d5-pawn falls. In fact we can even toy with the idea of playing ...Nxc2 and ... b4 here, and only recapture the d5-pawn later.} 
