[White "2) Accelerated Panov With a Rook Sac"]
[Black "Accelerated Panov - 5. Bb5+ Bd7 #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. c4 {The hallmark move of the Accelerated Panov.} 
2. d5
3. cxd5 {I would just like to point your attention to the fact that if White uses the move order3.exd5, Stockfish actually thinks the gambit3...Nf6!?4.dxc6Nxc6gives Black full compensation for the pawn. Something worth looking into.} 
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6 {Now White's main independent options are5.Qa4+and5.Bb5+, but he can also play5.Nc3(which has limited independent value) or transpose to a regular Panov with5.d4.} 
5. Bb5+ {Against this move it's also possible to play enterprisingly with 5... Bd7. However, this might be less surprising to your opponent, as here 5... Bd7 is not such a rare move (though still played 2.5 times less than 5... Nbd7).} 
5. Bd7
6. Bc4 {The only real move with which White can hope to hold on to the d5-pawn for some time. Now Black can and should make use of the placement of his bishop on d7.} 
6. b5 {We can abuse White's bishop to gain some space.} 
7. Bb3 {If at any time White plays Be2, we can just continue ...Nxd5 and enjoy the better pawn structure.} 
7. a5 {At this point7...g6is a good alternative, just finishing kingside development and only then continuing with ...a5-a4 and ...Na6-c7 etc. However, immediately pushing the queenside pawns is more fun.At this point we'll look at four possible continuations by White:8.Nf3,8.Nc3,8.a4and the main move8.a3.} 
8. a3 {The main move and the move which was seen in a few high level games, like a rapid game between Nigel Short and Anatoly Karpov. White prepares a square on a2 for his bishop to retreat to.} 
8. a4 {This seems to be a very rare move - I could only find one game with it. However, it looks to be Black's best bet (in conjunction with the next move).} 
9. Ba2
9. b4 {An interesting novelty. The problem is that a slow approach with9...g6is, well, just too slow; a sample line would be9...g610.Nf3Bg711.O-OO-O12.Nc3Na613.d4when the issue is that we can't play ...b4 anymore without dropping the a4-pawn to Nxa4, while13...Nc714.Ne5Be815.Qf3doesn't see us get the d5-pawn back either.So instead Black should confuse White on the queenside immediately! We're threatening 10...b3 and there are only two acceptable replies, 10. Bc4 and 10. axb4.} 
10. Bc4
10. Qc7 {(10...Qc8amounts to the same thing.) Here a slow approach won't work:10...g611.axb4Bg712.Nf3O-O13.Nc3Na614.b5and it's not clear how Black is going to get the pawn(s) back.} 
11. d3
11. Qb7 {The point of 10... Qc7 or 10... Qc8 - next we'll capture on d5. In this line our a4-pawn is a bit vulnerable, though, and with accurate play White will be able to win it.} 
12. Nf3 {This seems to be the only try that leads to some advantage. The point will become clear soon enough.} 
12. Nxd5 {Note that in this line with 8. a3 we have to develop with ...e6 and ...Bd6 usually, as we don't have the time for ...g6 etc.} 
13. O-O
13. e6 {For example13...g6?!14.Ne5Bg715.Nxf7!is problematic.} 
14. Ne5
14. Bd6 {14...Be7is comparable, but I think the bishop is better placed on d6. Now (if White wants to achieve something) the next moves are more or less forced.} 
15. Bxd5
15. Qxd5
16. Nxd7
16. Nxd7
17. axb4 {So far this makes sense. Now we see the problem for Black: a4 is hanging and it's nearly impossible to cover, as White will play Nc3 next.Here Black has a choice between17...Qb5, which leads to an endgame, and17...O-O, keeping queens on the board.} 
17. Qb5 {This move leads to an endgame.} 
18. Nc3
18. Qxb4
19. Rxa4
19. Rxa4
20. Qxa4 {I suppose White can keep queens on with20.Nxa4, but it's hardly an improvement after20...O-O.} 
20. Qxa4
21. Nxa4
21. Ke7 {White has an extra pawn, but here too the question is really how he will make progress and hold on to that pawn. For Black a natural continuation is ...Rb8 or ...Ra8 and then ...Ne5.} 
