10. axb4 {Note that10.b3?Nxd5is just bad for White.} 
10. Na6 {The point of the early ...b4. Now we can plant the knight on b4, whether White moves the pawn forward or not.} 
11. b5 {An attempt to (at least temporarily) keep hold of the extra material. However, White needs to be careful here.} 
11. Nb4 {Now we're already threatening ...Nd3+, and after12.Nc3?there is even12...Bf5!13.Bb1Bxb114.Rxb1Nd3+followed by ...Nxd5 with a clear advantage.} 
12. Bc4 {12.d3is the other move. Among other things, I like12...Nxa213.Rxa2Nxd514.Rxa4Bxb515.Rxa8Qxa8when Black has good compensation due to his control over the light squares.} 
12. Nfxd5
13. Rxa4 {This seems like the only challenging move. It gets tricky for White though.} 
13. Rxa4
14. Qxa4
14. Qc8 {With a nasty pin. Note that we're also introducing ...Nd3+ as an idea.} 
15. Na3
15. e6 {Covering both knights, and now ...Nb6 will pretty much always be our next move.} 
16. Qb3 {Another line is16.Nf3Nb617.Qb3Nxc418.Qxc4Qxc419.Nxc4Bxb520.b3and now Stockfish thinks the game will end in a draw with20...Nd3+21.Ke2Nf4+22.Kf1Nd3etc.} 
16. Nb6
17. d3 {Now Black has only one good, forcing continuation.} 
17. Nxd3+
18. Qxd3
18. Bxa3 {The point, removing the defender of the c4-bishop.} 
19. bxa3
19. Qxc4
20. Qxc4
20. Nxc4 {Black will ultimately regain the pawn, for instance:21.a4Ke722.Ne2Ra823.Nc3Nb6and ...Nxa4 is next.} 
