3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6 {Now White's main independent options are5.Qa4+and5.Bb5+, but he can also play5.Nc3(which has limited independent value) or transpose to a regular Panov with5.d4.} 
5. Qa4+
5. Bd7
6. Qb3 {This is the reason that 5... Bd7 is generally considered to be inaccurate, as Black isn't getting the d5-pawn back easily and the attack on b7 is annoying to deal with as well. However (with the help of the engine) it turns out Black is in fine shape actually - provided he knows how to sacrifice some material here.} 
6. e6 {Buckle up, because we're going to sacrifice material! Now there are various ways in which White can continue:1. White takes on b7 and then takes the a8-rook;2. White takes on b7 but declines the rook;3. White takes the e6-pawn and then takes on b7;4. White takes the e6-pawn and then doesn't take on b7;5. White doesn't grab any material at all.It turns out  (according to the computer) that only option 4 is acceptable for White, as it leads to an endgame where White is a pawn up (but Black has enough compensation). All the others give Black at least some edge, and there is lots of opportunity for White to lose directly out of the opening. And 6... e6 is practically a novelty! So you can be reasonably sure that your opponent will be out of book at this point. This is what makes this line very attractive to me.} 
7. Nc3 {Let's start with White not grabbing any of the pawns at all. The issue with this approach is that White is left with an IQP (usually) and the queen is misplaced on b3, or rather there are more important moves White should have played instead of putting the queen on b3.} 
7. Nxd5 {In most other lines we recapture7...exd5, but here that would lead to a sterile symmetrical position after8.d4!Bd69.Nf3O-O10.Be2etc. One difference is that in this line White can simply answer10...Re8with castling, while after our7...Nxd58.Nxd5exd5,with the extra pair of knights exchanged, the e2-bishop is unguarded and thus White finds it more difficult to finish development.} 
8. Nxd5 {8.Qxb7?is poorly timed here. After8...Nc6Black already has a winning initiative, with a combination of ...Ndb4, ...Nd4 and ...Rb8 coming. For instance9.Qb3Nd410.Qd1Nb4, or9.Nf3Ndb4followed by ...Rb8.} 
8. exd5 {Now we should check three continuations: White grabbing b7, White grabbing d5 and White just developing the kingside.} 
9. Qxb7 {This time the grab on b7 loses directly.} 
9. Nc6 {There is already a direct threat:10.--Rb811.Qa6Nb4followed by a fork on c2.} 
10. Qb3
10. Bc5 {This is Black's ideal active development, though moves like10...Rb8and10...Bd6should also do the job.} 
11. Nf3 {Or11.Qxd5Qe7+12.Be2Rc8and ...Nb4.} 
11. O-O
12. Be2
12. Re8
13. Qd1
13. Qe7 {White isn't getting castled without losing material, and ...Nd4 is next.} 
