3. cxd5 {I would just like to point your attention to the fact that if White uses the move order3.exd5, Stockfish actually thinks the gambit3...Nf6!?4.dxc6Nxc6gives Black full compensation for the pawn. Something worth looking into.} 
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6 {Now White's main independent options are5.Qa4+and5.Bb5+, but he can also play5.Nc3(which has limited independent value) or transpose to a regular Panov with5.d4.} 
5. Qa4+
5. Bd7
6. Qb3 {This is the reason that 5... Bd7 is generally considered to be inaccurate, as Black isn't getting the d5-pawn back easily and the attack on b7 is annoying to deal with as well. However (with the help of the engine) it turns out Black is in fine shape actually - provided he knows how to sacrifice some material here.} 
6. e6 {Buckle up, because we're going to sacrifice material! Now there are various ways in which White can continue:1. White takes on b7 and then takes the a8-rook;2. White takes on b7 but declines the rook;3. White takes the e6-pawn and then takes on b7;4. White takes the e6-pawn and then doesn't take on b7;5. White doesn't grab any material at all.It turns out  (according to the computer) that only option 4 is acceptable for White, as it leads to an endgame where White is a pawn up (but Black has enough compensation). All the others give Black at least some edge, and there is lots of opportunity for White to lose directly out of the opening. And 6... e6 is practically a novelty! So you can be reasonably sure that your opponent will be out of book at this point. This is what makes this line very attractive to me.} 
7. Qxb7 {This has to be one of the main moves, but objectively it's not very good.} 
7. exd5 {Only like this! Let's see why by looking at an important continuation: After7...Nxd5?8.Qxa8Bc59.Qb7Bb610.Nc3!O-O11.Nxd5White's queen is getting out. In the same position where we have played 7... exd5 instead, we would be able to answer11.Nxd5with11...Re8+12.Be2Bc6and White's queen is trapped.} 
8. Bb5 {Objectively the best continuation, though it's not a very human move. However, White often has great problems developing the kingside pieces satisfactorily in this line, and by playing Bb5 White can exchange one of these problem pieces and put the other on e2.} 
8. Bd6 {In this case8...Bc5seems less accurate, as after9.Ne2White can win a tempo with d4 next.} 
9. Ne2 {The issue is that9.Nf3Qe7+!would ruin White's dream of castling.Also, note that9.Qxa8??makes no sense anymore here, just giving up the b5-bishop. The most accurate refutation is9...Qe7+!10.Ne2Bxb5and 11... Bc6, or10.Be2Bc6,winning the queen in both cases.} 
9. O-O
10. O-O {It's not very likely that White plays this, but I wanted to show the refutation.} 
10. Bxh2+
11. Kxh2
11. Ng4+
12. Kg3 {12.Kg1Qh4is fairly obvious, and12.Kh3Nxf2+should win for Black as well.} 
12. Qg5 {Now play likely continues13.f4Qg614.f5Qg5and ...Ne3+ next is crushing.} 
