6. Qb3 {This is the reason that 5... Bd7 is generally considered to be inaccurate, as Black isn't getting the d5-pawn back easily and the attack on b7 is annoying to deal with as well. However (with the help of the engine) it turns out Black is in fine shape actually - provided he knows how to sacrifice some material here.} 
6. e6 {Buckle up, because we're going to sacrifice material! Now there are various ways in which White can continue:1. White takes on b7 and then takes the a8-rook;2. White takes on b7 but declines the rook;3. White takes the e6-pawn and then takes on b7;4. White takes the e6-pawn and then doesn't take on b7;5. White doesn't grab any material at all.It turns out  (according to the computer) that only option 4 is acceptable for White, as it leads to an endgame where White is a pawn up (but Black has enough compensation). All the others give Black at least some edge, and there is lots of opportunity for White to lose directly out of the opening. And 6... e6 is practically a novelty! So you can be reasonably sure that your opponent will be out of book at this point. This is what makes this line very attractive to me.} 
7. Qxb7 {This has to be one of the main moves, but objectively it's not very good.} 
7. exd5 {Only like this! Let's see why by looking at an important continuation: After7...Nxd5?8.Qxa8Bc59.Qb7Bb610.Nc3!O-O11.Nxd5White's queen is getting out. In the same position where we have played 7... exd5 instead, we would be able to answer11.Nxd5with11...Re8+12.Be2Bc6and White's queen is trapped.} 
8. Qxa8 {Taking up the gauntlet.} 
8. Bc5 {Developing actively and more importantly, guarding the a7-pawn for the moment. We're already threatening ...Bc6 so White's acceptable replies are limited.} 
9. Qb7
9. Bb6 {L'Ami's comment: 'leads to fascinating complications - a rook down'. In fact Stockfish assesses it as clearly better for Black, and that's assuming White plays correctly! Long story short, White's queen will eventually be trapped. The question is how much material he'll get for it. The answer is: two rooks and a pawn, but with Black having far superior piece coordination, which is why Black is better.Now after9...Bb6Black threatens ...Bc6, so we should only check moves that counter this threat:10.Nc3,10.Ba6and10.a4(the main move).} 
10. a4 {The best way for White to prepare Bb5.} 
10. O-O {As usual. Now we threaten ... Bc6, so White's reply is forced.} 
11. Bb5
11. Re8+ {Developing with tempo, and we force White to make a decision regarding his king. Now there are three possible moves:12.Kf1,12.Kd1and12.Ne2. I don't think we need to discuss12.Be2?Bc6.} 
12. Ne2 {Finally, the main and most obvious move.} 
12. Rxe2+ {We're down a rook, so let's sacrifice another exchange!} 
13. Bxe2 {13.Kxe2?loses directly to13...Qe7+and a check with the d7-bishop next, depending on where White's king goes, followed by ...Qxb7.} 
13. Bc6 {The point - White's light-squared bishop has been lured away and we can finally trap the queen.} 
14. Qxb6
14. Qxb6 {Let's look at a few deeper lines if my positional assessment wasn't convincing enough for you.} 
15. O-O
15. d4
16. d3
16. Qb7 {Forcing White to weaken the kingside. This is similar to the line with 15. a5 that we've examined earlier. Now White should play 17. f3, when play is similar to that line. Let's look at a different, seemingly logical try for White.} 
17. g3
17. Bg2 {A nice regrouping.} 
18. Re1
18. Bh3 {White is forced to play f3 anyway. In case of19.Bf1Bxf120.Rxf1Black can target the d3-pawn with20...Nc6and ...Nb4 or ...Ne5.} 
19. f3
19. Nc6
20. Nd2
20. Nb4 {White is in huge trouble with ...Nc2 and ...Nd5-e3 coming next.} 
