[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation - 7...e5!? in the Mainline"]
[Black "Chapter 3 Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3
4. Nc6
5. c3
5. Nf6
6. Bf4
6. Bg4 {The mainline of the exchange variation.} 
7. Qb3 {Now the main moves are7...Qd7and7...Qc8, while7...Na5has also at times been an important try by Black.} 
7. e5 {This weird-looking move started being played now and then by strong players from 2018 onwards - I think mainly because if you let Stockfish run long enough, it will give 7... e5 as a valid option! It looks crazy, leaving b7 unprotected while hanging another pawn on e5, so let's dig into the details. White needs to make a choice immediately.} 
8. h3 {8.Qxb7This pawn grab of course has to be analyzed, though it has hardly ever been played. After8...exf49.Qxc6+Bd710.Qa6Qb8!11.b3Bd612.Nf3O-O13.O-OQc7Black has good compensation. White's queen is offside and it's hard for White to develop the queenside without returning the extra pawn.8.dxe5The most played move and also the most straightforward.8...Nh5One of the ideas of 7... e5 - White's bishop is harassed and then we can retake on e5.9.Be3Nxe510.Bb5+Nc6The pieces may look a bit strangely positioned right now, but usually after a few more moves we get a fairly typical IQP position where Black has his fair share of the chances. If you don't want to play with an IQP, the 7... e5 variation is not for you.} 
 {I think 8. h3 is the critical try. Let's look at how events develop.} 8. exf4 {Stockfish insists that8...Na5is slightly stronger, but I'm not convinced for reasons I'll explain in more detail in the theory section.} 
9. hxg4
9. Qe7+ {This seems Black's strongest setup, gaining a tempo on White's king to be able to castle long next.} 
10. Kf1
10. O-O-O
11. Nd2
11. g5 {At the time I analyzed this move it was a novelty, although by now via transposition we arrive at a game Shubin-Pershin which was played in March 2022. The move 11... g5 is an improvement over Shankland-Liang from the 2018 US championship. With ...g5 we fix the g4-pawn in place so that we can then attack it with ...h5, opening up the kingside against White's king.Shankland-Liang went11...g6?!12.Re1Qc713.g5!and White obtained a very strong hold on the position.} 
12. Re1
12. Qc7
13. Ngf3
13. h5
14. gxh5
14. g4 {This is stronger than14...Nxh5from Shubin-Pershin. According to the computer White is doing quite well, but I believe his position looks very dangerous.} 
