[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation - 7...e5!? in the Mainline"]
[Black "Exchange Variation 7... e5 - 8. Bxe5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {In this chapter I'll only consider the mainline of the exchange variation. I don't think the alternatives (bar4.c4,the Panov) are really challenging, as they allow Black to easily develop his c8-bishop to either f5 or g4 before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.} 
4. Nc6 {The d4-pawn is hanging.} 
5. c3
5. Nf6
6. Bf4 {At this point White has an alternative in6.h3,trying to frustrate the development of the c8-bishop, when practice has shown that Black is fine after6...e5!7.dxe5Nxe5.I refer you to Keep it Simple for Black and LTR: Caro-Kann for more details.} 
6. Bg4
7. Qb3 {Now the mainline continues7...Qd7, while7...Qc8and7...Na5have also seen regular play. Instead I want to offer a move that will likely come as a big surprise to your opponent.} 
7. e5 {Quite a shocker - Black leaves the b7-pawn hanging, and doesn't White currently control the e5-square, making the e5-pawn an offering as well? Yet it works out well enough. The point is that after White captures the e5-pawn there is always ...Nh5, the f4-bishop retreats and Black can recapture the pawn on e5. Meanwhile White can grab the b7-pawn, but due to his lack of coordination/lack of development, there always seems to be (at least) enough compensation for Black.} 
8. Bxe5 {A poor way of capturing on e5.} 
8. Qe7 {The problem is that White will lose the bishop pair for nothing and is in danger of being worse.} 
9. Ne2 {9.Qa4Bd7doesn't change the situation.9.f4?!is even worse, as after9...Nh5!the f4-pawn is hanging and the bishop on e5 is in danger of being trapped with ...f6.} 
9. Nxe5
10. dxe5
10. Qxe5 {The pawn is back, Black has the bishop pair and White has trouble getting castled.} 
11. Qxb7 {This capture already loses.} 
11. Rb8
12. Qxa7 {12.Qa6Bc5and12.Qc6+Bd713.Qa6Bc514.O-ONg4see Black create decisive threats against White's king.} 
12. Bxe2 {The most accurate move order.12...Rxb2?13.Qa8+Rb814.Bb5+is much less clear.} 
13. Bxe2
13. Rxb2 {Threatening mate.} 
14. Qa8+ {White has various ways of playing and giving checks, but the gist of the matter is this: If White keeps giving checks with the queen, Black's king will find a safe square on e6 (and then a check on the 6th rank can be answered ...Bd6).Meanwhile, if White plays something like14.Qa6or14.Nd2,the move ...Bd6 is best, threatening to castle while White is still stuck defending the bishop on e2.} 
14. Kd7
15. Qa4+
15. Ke6 {The king is relatively safe here. As mentioned, another check on a6 would now be answered by ...Bd6.} 
16. Nd2
16. Qxc3 {White has to give up a piece in order to get castled. Note that17.Rd1?Rxd2!18.Rxd2Ne4is directly over, as is17.Qd1?Rxd2!18.Qxd2Qxa1+. Finally, note the continuation17.O-ORxd218.Rfe1Kf5!when Black's king is perfectly safe and Black is threatening ...Rxe2.} 
