1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {In this chapter I'll only consider the mainline of the exchange variation. I don't think the alternatives (bar4.c4,the Panov) are really challenging, as they allow Black to easily develop his c8-bishop to either f5 or g4 before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.} 
4. Nc6 {The d4-pawn is hanging.} 
5. c3
5. Nf6
6. Bf4 {At this point White has an alternative in6.h3,trying to frustrate the development of the c8-bishop, when practice has shown that Black is fine after6...e5!7.dxe5Nxe5.I refer you to Keep it Simple for Black and LTR: Caro-Kann for more details.} 
6. Bg4
7. Qb3 {Now the mainline continues7...Qd7, while7...Qc8and7...Na5have also seen regular play. Instead I want to offer a move that will likely come as a big surprise to your opponent.} 
7. e5 {Quite a shocker - Black leaves the b7-pawn hanging, and doesn't White currently control the e5-square, making the e5-pawn an offering as well? Yet it works out well enough. The point is that after White captures the e5-pawn there is always ...Nh5, the f4-bishop retreats and Black can recapture the pawn on e5. Meanwhile White can grab the b7-pawn, but due to his lack of coordination/lack of development, there always seems to be (at least) enough compensation for Black.} 
8. Qxb7 {This is possible, but the lines are rather difficult to play for White, who is on a materialistic hunt.} 
8. exf4 {This seems slightly more accurate than8...Rb8,which is however also a playable move. The point is that we want to keep the b8-square for our queen!} 
9. Qxc6+ {9.Bb5is technically possible, but a very computerish way of playing. The line continues9...Rb810.Bxc6+Nd711.Bxd7+Bxd712.Qxd5Rxb2.Next up Black will play ...Bb5 with very active pieces.} 
9. Bd7 {Now White's queen has two squares.} 
10. Qa6 {10.Qb7?is the wrong square, though of course the move makes no sense either as it gives Black a valuable tempo with10...Rb8. After11.Qa6Qc7!Black's initiative is too strong. There is the threat of12.--Rb613.Qa5Re6+with a discovered attack on White's queen, while12.Ne2Rxb213.O-Of314.gxf3Bd6gives Black a crushing attack.} 
10. Qb8 {This is the point of not playing ...Rb8 yet. The queen creates a rather annoying threat of ...Qxb2. White has a choice:11.b3,11.b4, or giving Black the b2-pawn with either11.Nd2or11.Nf3.} 
11. b4
11. Qc7 {The queen has done her job on b8 and now focuses on the c-file. We are setting up a direct threat of ...Bxb4.} 
12. Nf3
12. Bxb4 {Regaining the sacrificed pawn.} 
13. O-O
13. Bd6
14. Re1+
14. Kf8 {This is not an issue for Black. We are getting castled by hand.} 
15. Nbd2
15. g6 {Next is ...Kg7. Black is fine.} 
