[White "3) Exchange Variation - 7...e5!? in the Mainline"]
[Black "Exchange Variation 7... e5 - 8. h3 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {In this chapter I'll only consider the mainline of the exchange variation. I don't think the alternatives (bar4.c4,the Panov) are really challenging, as they allow Black to easily develop his c8-bishop to either f5 or g4 before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.} 
4. Nc6 {The d4-pawn is hanging.} 
5. c3
5. Nf6
6. Bf4 {At this point White has an alternative in6.h3,trying to frustrate the development of the c8-bishop, when practice has shown that Black is fine after6...e5!7.dxe5Nxe5.I refer you to Keep it Simple for Black and LTR: Caro-Kann for more details.} 
6. Bg4
7. Qb3 {Now the mainline continues7...Qd7, while7...Qc8and7...Na5have also seen regular play. Instead I want to offer a move that will likely come as a big surprise to your opponent.} 
7. e5 {Quite a shocker - Black leaves the b7-pawn hanging, and doesn't White currently control the e5-square, making the e5-pawn an offering as well? Yet it works out well enough. The point is that after White captures the e5-pawn there is always ...Nh5, the f4-bishop retreats and Black can recapture the pawn on e5. Meanwhile White can grab the b7-pawn, but due to his lack of coordination/lack of development, there always seems to be (at least) enough compensation for Black.} 
8. h3 {This subtle in-between move is the second most played move after the straightforward 8. dxe5, and has been the choice of a number of high-rated players such as Sam Shankland. Black doesn't have a good retreating move with the bishop (as then White would get a significantly better version of the capture on e5), which limits the choice to 8... Na5 and 8... exf4.} 
8. exf4 {I think we should just take the bishop.8...Na5gets a higher score from the computer but I don't think it leads to pleasant positions for Black, as explained in the preceding informational line.} 
9. hxg4
9. Qe7+ {This is an important point. We don't go for the g4-pawn (at least not immediately), but first want to castle queenside as soon as possible.} 
10. Kf1 {This seems the most pointed answer to 9... Qe7+. The king is relatively safe on f1, and White can quickly activate the queenside with Nd2 and Re1 next, when both rooks will be on open files.} 
10. O-O-O {Castling long was the point behind ...Qe7+. Bad for Black would be10...Nxg4?11.Nd2Qd7(11...O-O-O?runs into12.Bf5+as we've seen earlier)12.Re1+Be713.Nh3and this seems a poor version for Black compared to the lines we'll see.} 
11. Nd2 {11.g5would be too early in view of11...Ne4!threatening ...Nxg5, as we've seen in a similar variation.A few games have reached the position after 11. Nd2, notably Shankland - Liang, from the US championship in 2018. Here I'd like to suggest an aggressive improvement for Black.} 
11. g5 {The aforementioned game continued11...g6,when White took control over the e4-square with12.Re1Qc7before pushing13.g5,so that Black didn't have the resource ...Ne4 anymore and was just worse.Similarly,11...Kb8runs into12.Re1Qc713.g5with a clear advantage to White.With11...g5the situation becomes completely different. First of, the push g4-g5 is directly prevented. Secondly and more importantly, however, is that we fix the g4-pawn for a future advance with ...h5 and ...g4, opening lines and pushing pawns against White's king. Objectively, Stockfish thinks White has some advantage here (around +0.7) but practically, for a human being I think this is very hard to play as White.In general, what Black wants to play next is: ...h5, ...Qc7 and ...Bd6, then take on g4. In some cases the dark-squared bishop might be developed to h6 or g7 instead.} 
12. Ndf3 {Stockfish's preferred move, but this is extremely subtle. Why put this knight on f3 and not the one from g1? The main reason seems to be that the d2-knight had no future as the d5-pawn controls c4 and e4, while the knight on g1 at least has some defensive functions if for instance the h-file opens up.Regardless, though, I think most of our moves would be the same against 12. Ngf3 as they are against 12. Ndf3.} 
12. h5 {We'll play this move against most of White's tries.} 
13. Qc2 {Again the top computer choice, again rather subtle. Why not start with 13. Re1? The point is that if Black now replies13...Qc7?!, then14.Nxg5Bh615.Nh7!is very strong for White, who just seems to be winning material on the kingside for not much compensation.} 
13. Rh6 {Perhaps not the top engine choice, but this move makes the most sense to me. It's a very concrete way of preparing the capture ...hxg4, as the black rook is now defended by the bishop on f8.13...Bg7and13...Bh6are worth considering too.} 
14. Re1
14. Qc7
15. Nxg5 {This seems a likely continuation. As mentioned, we can now take on g4.15.Bb5is also interesting, with the idea to take on c6 and establish a knight on e5, but it relinquishes control over e4 in return, so15...Ne4seems an adequate reply.} 
15. hxg4 {Next we'll see some exchanges.} 
16. Rxh6
16. Bxh6
17. Nh7 {White is systematically removing support of the g4-pawn.} 
17. Nxh7
18. Bxh7 {White is threatening Bf5+ or even Qf5+, so we have to step out.} 
18. Kb8 {At this point White can keep some advantage with19.Qf5,asking us what we're going to do with the g4-pawn. The whole line feels very artificial and inhuman though. I guess the bottom line is - don't play this variation against a 2022 computer engine :-)} 
