6. Bg4
7. Qb3 {Now the mainline continues7...Qd7, while7...Qc8and7...Na5have also seen regular play. Instead I want to offer a move that will likely come as a big surprise to your opponent.} 
7. e5 {Quite a shocker - Black leaves the b7-pawn hanging, and doesn't White currently control the e5-square, making the e5-pawn an offering as well? Yet it works out well enough. The point is that after White captures the e5-pawn there is always ...Nh5, the f4-bishop retreats and Black can recapture the pawn on e5. Meanwhile White can grab the b7-pawn, but due to his lack of coordination/lack of development, there always seems to be (at least) enough compensation for Black.} 
8. dxe5 {This is the main move by some margin.} 
8. Nh5 {Otherwise 7... e5 wouldn't make sense. We do have to get the e5-pawn back in one way or another.} 
9. Be3 {The main move, soberly retreating the bishop.} 
9. Nxe5 {At this point there is nothing but to just take the pawn back.} 
10. Bb5+
10. Nc6 {We've arrived at the starting position of the main line of 7... e5. We have an IQP position where both sides have somewhat weirdly placed pieces. White hasn't developed the knights yet. The e3-bishop is fine, while the b5-bishop would be best placed on g2 (or f3). For Black, the g4-bishop and c6-knight are placed well enough, but the h5-knight sticks out a bit, and we've yet to decide on a square for the f8-bishop.} 
11. h3 {This move has been played in a handful of games, but with a significant score for Black (6 draws and 5 black wins). It's probably not worth wasting a tempo on this move, as it also weakens the dark squares, making a setup involving ...Bd6 and then eventually ...Nf4 more annoying for White to deal with.} 
11. Be6 {Gaining a useful tempo due to the threat of ...d4.} 
12. Qd1 {12.Qa4is also possible, but Black has a decent choice -12...Bd7is the computer's choice,12...Rc8!?is also possible though it sacrifices the a7-pawn, and my personal choice would be12...Qc7followed by ...Bd6 and castling short.} 
12. Nf6 {The position significantly normalizes.} 
13. Nf3
13. Bd6
14. O-O
14. O-O {With a fairly normal IQP position which is probably equal. There is room for either White or Black to outplay the other player from here. For Black, notably all pieces are still on the board which should favor the player with the IQP (White would like to exchange all minor pieces).The high-rated blitz game Wei Yi - Navara continued:15.Nbd2Qd716.Re1a617.Bf1Rac818.Nb3Ne419.Nbd4Bb820.Qc1Qd621.Ne2.Up until here almost perfectly played by Navara, also demonstrating some typical ideas (for instance, playing ...Rac8 before setting up a battery on the b8-h2 diagonal). Now he mixed things up with21...d4?when22.Bf4!was a strong answer. Instead,21...f6!would have given Black the advantage, preparing ...Ne5 when White has to either exchange on e5 or further weaken the kingside in view of ...Nxf3+ followed by mate on h2.} 
