11. Nd2 {This is given by GM Jarmula in his course 'Combat the Caro-Kann with 3.exd5'. It makes good sense - White wants to develop with Ngf3 next without allowing Black to double the pawns on f3.Indeed, if11.Nf3?!Bxf312.gxf3Be7it's hard to see White ever castling kingside.} 
11. Nf6 {11...Be6is another natural move, but I don't really like the positions after12.Qa4Bd713.Ngf3a614.Bxc6Bxc615.Qc2,though here too I think Black is pretty much equal. However, I'd like to keep the bishop on g4 for now unless we absolutely need to retreat it. If we want to develop the bishop to d6 next, it's necessary to guard the d5-pawn with our knight.Notably GM Alexandra Kosteniuk played11...Nf6twice against GM Anna Muzychuk in a blitz match on chess.com, and scored a win and a draw.} 
12. Ngf3
12. Bd6 {This is how we want to develop. Castling is up next.} 
13. O-O
13. O-O {If you don't like the upcoming pawn sac(s), you could play13...h6here and only then castle, though White could still transpose to it anyway with14.Bd4!?O-O15.Bxf6Qxf616.Qxd5.} 
14. Bg5 {This has to be critical. After most other moves Black would play ...h6 and prevent this annoying move.} 
14. h6 {We should immediately force White to clarify the situation - does he want to grab a pawn, or does he want to try to maintain the pin?} 
15. Bh4 {This is also critical. At this point we need to force the ...d4 breakthrough.} 
15. a6
16. Bd3 {Or16.Bxc6bxc617.Qa4Bd7with an equal-ish position.16.Be2g517.Bg3d418.cxd4Bxg319.hxg3Nxd420.Nxd4Bxe221.Nxe2Qxd2is very similar to 16. Bd3.} 
16. g5 {A bit weakening, but if we can play this under good circumstances it should be considered. In case of16...Re817.Rfe1White has a small edge as the annoying pin on the f6-knight remains.} 
17. Bg3
17. d4 {The point. Note that we don't really have to be worried about18.Qxb7?at any point here, as18...Na5would trap the queen.} 
18. cxd4 {18.Nxd4Nxd419.cxd4Bxg3amounts to the same thing.} 
18. Bxg3
19. hxg3 {19.fxg3?!is sometimes an idea for White in such positions, trying to make use of the pressure on the f-file, but here it weakens the e3-square:19...Nxd420.Qc3Nxf3+21.Nxf3Qb6+22.Kh1Nd5and Black might have some initiative.} 
19. Nxd4
20. Nxd4
20. Qxd4
21. Nf3
21. Qa7 {This looks a bit awkward, but the queen is safe from harassment here and we're ready to get the rooks into the game. Other moves to help stabilize the position are ...Kg7, ...Be6 and ...b5.Instead,21....Qd622.Rad1actually is a bit awkward for Black.} 
