[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation - 7...e5!? in the Mainline"]
[Black "Exchange Variation 7... e5 - 8. dxe5 #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {In this chapter I'll only consider the mainline of the exchange variation. I don't think the alternatives (bar4.c4,the Panov) are really challenging, as they allow Black to easily develop his c8-bishop to either f5 or g4 before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.} 
4. Nc6 {The d4-pawn is hanging.} 
5. c3
5. Nf6
6. Bf4 {At this point White has an alternative in6.h3,trying to frustrate the development of the c8-bishop, when practice has shown that Black is fine after6...e5!7.dxe5Nxe5.I refer you to Keep it Simple for Black and LTR: Caro-Kann for more details.} 
6. Bg4
7. Qb3 {Now the mainline continues7...Qd7, while7...Qc8and7...Na5have also seen regular play. Instead I want to offer a move that will likely come as a big surprise to your opponent.} 
7. e5 {Quite a shocker - Black leaves the b7-pawn hanging, and doesn't White currently control the e5-square, making the e5-pawn an offering as well? Yet it works out well enough. The point is that after White captures the e5-pawn there is always ...Nh5, the f4-bishop retreats and Black can recapture the pawn on e5. Meanwhile White can grab the b7-pawn, but due to his lack of coordination/lack of development, there always seems to be (at least) enough compensation for Black.} 
8. dxe5 {This is the main move by some margin.} 
8. Nh5 {Otherwise 7... e5 wouldn't make sense. We do have to get the e5-pawn back in one way or another.} 
9. Be3 {The main move, soberly retreating the bishop.} 
9. Nxe5 {At this point there is nothing but to just take the pawn back.} 
10. Bb5+
10. Nc6 {We've arrived at the starting position of the main line of 7... e5. We have an IQP position where both sides have somewhat weirdly placed pieces. White hasn't developed the knights yet. The e3-bishop is fine, while the b5-bishop would be best placed on g2 (or f3). For Black, the g4-bishop and c6-knight are placed well enough, but the h5-knight sticks out a bit, and we've yet to decide on a square for the f8-bishop.} 
11. Nd2 {This is given by GM Jarmula in his course 'Combat the Caro-Kann with 3.exd5'. It makes good sense - White wants to develop with Ngf3 next without allowing Black to double the pawns on f3.Indeed, if11.Nf3?!Bxf312.gxf3Be7it's hard to see White ever castling kingside.} 
11. Nf6 {11...Be6is another natural move, but I don't really like the positions after12.Qa4Bd713.Ngf3a614.Bxc6Bxc615.Qc2,though here too I think Black is pretty much equal. However, I'd like to keep the bishop on g4 for now unless we absolutely need to retreat it. If we want to develop the bishop to d6 next, it's necessary to guard the d5-pawn with our knight.Notably GM Alexandra Kosteniuk played11...Nf6twice against GM Anna Muzychuk in a blitz match on chess.com, and scored a win and a draw.} 
12. Ngf3
12. Bd6 {This is how we want to develop. Castling is up next.} 
13. O-O
13. O-O {If you don't like the upcoming pawn sac(s), you could play13...h6here and only then castle, though White could still transpose to it anyway with14.Bd4!?O-O15.Bxf6Qxf616.Qxd5.} 
14. Bg5 {This has to be critical. After most other moves Black would play ...h6 and prevent this annoying move.} 
14. h6 {We should immediately force White to clarify the situation - does he want to grab a pawn, or does he want to try to maintain the pin?} 
15. Bxf6
15. Qxf6
16. Qxd5 {White should take. If he hesitates, Black can continue with ...Rfd8 or ...Rad8 and just stand better because White gave up the bishop pair for no good reason.} 
16. Rfd8 {With an obvious threat. At this point White should take on c6 or play Qe4.If he retreats meekly with17.Qc4or17.Qb3,17...Ne5already gives Black a strong attack.} 
17. Qe4 {Retreating with a tempo on our bishop. Play becomes quite forcing now.} 
17. Bf5 {A tempo move.} 
18. Qh4 {Presumably this is White's idea.18.Qa4Ne5is similar, though.} 
18. g5 {Another tempo move. Clearly we don't want to exchange queens.} 
19. Qa4
19. Ne5 {Necessary as most other moves allow White to play Ne4.} 
20. Nxe5
20. Qxe5
21. Nf3
21. Qf6 {At this point White has many possible moves, while Black's compensation for the pawn in the form of the bishop pair should be clear. Black has a possible kingside attack, though it's not the main focus. Probably our next moves will be ...a6 and ...b5. If possible we could reroute the light-squared bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal, but if not, it's fine on the b1-h7 one as well.} 
