19. Nd4 {Now19.Qxc6is possible. An approximate continuation is19...Rab820.Ne4Qe721.Nxd6Rxd6followed by ...Rxb2, when Black has good compensation for the pawn. If you really want to keep the bishop pair on the board,19...Bd5!?is an interesting idea as well, though the computer prefers White's position there. I don't think a human player would touch White's position with a barge pole though.} 
19. Bd5 {Now the bishop pair is ideally positioned. The only annoying thing is that White can more or less force the queens off next.} 
20. Qf5 {If not for this move White's position would be questionable.} 
20. Be5 {With good compensation for the pawn. A possible continuation is21.N2f3Qxf522.Nxf5Bf6when White probably has to allow ...Bxf3 followed by ... Rd2 next. Note that the immediate22...Bxf3?!23.gxf3Rd2is less strong, as after24.Rab1Rb8?White has25.Ne7+and 26. Nxc6.} 
