*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Panov Without Putting a Knight on f6"]
[Black "Chapter 4 Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4 {The Panov Attack still has a healthy following, even though it seems nowadays that Black can equalize in several different ways.} 
4. e6 {We need to play this move order for the particular variation I'm suggesting. This also means that one of the downsides is that you can't get this line on the board if White starts with the move order1.e4c62.c4d53.exd5cxd54.cxd5, so you can't make this line your full repertoire against the Panov.} 
5. Nc3
5. Bb4 {I noticed that GM Bartosz Socko played this move order a few times in 2021, albeit in rapid and blitz games. The idea is quite interesting: Black moves the bishop out first because he wants to put the knight on e7 instead of f6. If White at any moment exchanges on d5, we can retake with the pawn and reach a symmetrical structure where the knight is probably better on e7 than f6 (compare with the Exchange French, for instance, where Black often develops with ...Ne7 too in order to offer an exchange of bishops later with ...Bf5).} 
6. Nf3
6. Ne7 {In the same position with the knight on f6,7.cxd5is the main try here, being played about twice as often as the second move7.Bd3.Moving the bishop to d3 actually transposes to an important line in the 4. e3 Nimzo Indian after7...dxc48.Bxc4O-O9.O-Ob6.} 
7. Bd3 {There are almost no games with 6... Ne7, so it is hard to say what the mainline is. As mentioned, in the Panov line with the knight on f6, the move 7. cxd5 is more popular, but that clearly isn't critical here.7.cxd5exd5!This is my idea - whenever White takes on d5, we recapture with the pawn to reach a symmetrical position. I want to argue that Black's knight is better placed on e7 than f6 to defuse White's attempts to make something of his extra tempo in a symmetrical structure.} 
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4 {This is the only line where we do get to an IQP position. Essentially, after} 
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. b6 {we transpose to a well-known Nimzo-Indian line, but our knight is on e7 instead of f6. This does not automatically favor Black, but White's most important attempts in this Nimzo variation do rely on developing the bishop to g5, which looks decidedly less logical when our kingside knight is on e7 instead. My research seems to show that Black is okay. It just leads to interesting positions where one player can outplay the other.This is an almost entirely unexplored line (there are maybe one or two games in the current position), but I have modeled the theory section (particularly, White's possible/plausible choices) on the same position with the knight on f6 instead, which has been seen in thousands of games. If you want to learn more about the Nimzo line, it is featured from the Black side in one of the chapters of part 1 of GM Ganguly's Nimzo/Semi-Tarrasch repertoire.} 
