[White "4) Panov Without Putting a Knight on f6"]
[Black "Panov: Faux Nimzo with 10. Ne4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4
4. e6 {Perhaps not a super strange move, as ...e6-based setups are relatively common against the Panov, but usually Black starts by developing the g8-knight to remain flexible. The point of starting with 4... e6 only becomes clear on the next move.} 
5. Nc3 {5.cxd5exd5will inevitably transpose to our later 6. cxd5 or 7. cxd5 lines.In case of5.Nf3we can continue5...Bb4, when6.Nc3transposes while6.Bd2Bxd2+7.Qxd2dxc48.Bxc4Nf6is very comfortable for Black (here the knight is very comfortable on f6 as the dark-squared bishops have been traded).} 
5. Bb4 {This is why we started with 4... e6 - so we could develop the bishop to b4 immediately. But why move the bishop first? The point is that we want to play a ...Bb4 Panov but put the knight on e7 instead of on f6, so we had to get the bishop out first. But why do we want to put the knight on e7?Apart from surprise value, putting the knight on e7 instead of f6 has its own points. We'll need to consider what White usually does in a Panov with ...Bb4.Broadly speaking, in the variation1.e4c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.c4Nf65.Nc3e66.Nf3Bb4White has two main ways of playing. In case White plays7.cxd5(one of the main moves), with the knight on e7 we are better placed to answer7...exd5with a symmetrical position where I would argue Black's knight is better on e7 than on f6. With the knight on f6, White's most tempting plans have to do with moves like Ne5 and Bg5, both of which are less attractive when we can just kick the offending piece back with ...f6.The other main way of playing for White is7.Bd3dxc48.Bxc4O-O9.O-O,which leads to a position which can also arise via one of the main lines of the the Nimzo-Indian. In such positions, a key part of White's setup is Bg5, but this pin is much less of a problem with our knight on e7 instead of f6.} 
6. Nf3
6. Ne7 {This is the last possible moment for White to take on d5.} 
7. Bd3 {In the analogous position with the knight on f6 instead of e7, this is the only significant alternative to 7. cxd5.} 
7. dxc4 {As White has spent a tempo developing the d3-bishop, there is nothing to be gained for Black to delay the capture7...dxc4any longer. In fact, with the knight in e7 instead of f6,7...O-O?would be an immediate blunder due to the Greek gift8.Bxh7+!, while if we play a neutral developing move like7...Nbc6, we'd have to reckon with the advance8.c5!?among other things.} 
8. Bxc4
8. O-O {At this point White will castle 99.9% of the time, and then with the knight on f6 instead of e7, play has transposed to a popular variation of the 4. e3 Nimzo Indian (1.d4Nf62.c4e63.Nc3Bb44.e3O-O5.Bd3d56.Nf3dxc47.Bxc4c58.O-Ocxd49.exd4).As there are only a few games with ...Ne7 that have reached the current position, I'll mainly be drawing ideas for White from the analogous Nimzo-Indian line.Just be careful that in case of the immediate retreat9.Bd3White is actually threatening Bxh7+, e.g.9...b6?10.Bxh7+!Kxh711.Ng5+Kg612.h4!and Black is in trouble. This can be avoided by playing9...h6.} 
9. O-O
9. b6 {In the analogous Nimzo-Indian position White's main move now would be10.Bg5, while10.Qe2and10.Qb3are also popular lines. However, there are several independent options due to our knight being on e7 instead of f6 that we should check.} 
10. Ne4 {This is one way with which White could try to exploit our lack of control over e4. The knight moves over to the kingside and our bishop on b4 now looks a bit silly. However, this does cost White precious time while he hasn't fully developed all his pieces yet.} 
10. Bb7 {Now the knight is hanging and White has to decide what to do with it.} 
11. Neg5 {If White is going to move the knight again this is probably his best try. After all, with the knight on e7 instead of f6, h7 is a vulnerable point in our kingside.The less natural11.Nfg5!?is also possible, but it leads to a similar drawing variation. After11...h6White is losing a piece, but he can force a repetition of moves with12.a3!Bd613.Qg4!hxg514.Nxg5Nf515.Qh3Nh616.Qd3Nf5etc.Finally,11.Ng3?!is just too passive. We can continue11...Ng6and then ... Nc6, ...Be7-f6 etc.} 
11. h6 {Now going back to h3 would be an admission of failure for White.} 
12. Qd3 {Or12.a3Bd613.Qd3!Only this queen move justifies White's play, but it leads to a draw by force.} 
12. hxg5
13. Nxg5 {Now we have to block the checkmate threat.} 
13. Nf5 {13...Ng6?is not good due to14.Bxe6!.} 
14. Qh3 {14.g4?is not a good idea due to14...Qxd4.Sacrifices on e6 also don't work well:14.Nxe6fxe615.Bxe6+Kh816.Bxf5Qh4!17.g3Qf618.Be4Bxe419.Qxe4Nd7and the piece is stronger than the three pawns, while14.Bxe6?is even worse after14...fxe615.Nxe6Qd5!} 
14. Nh6 {If you really want to prolong the game,14...Re815.Qh7+Kf816.Qh8+Ke7is possible, but it's very tricky to handle. Stockfish evaluates that position as approximately equal. The move repetition with Nh6-f5-h6 is the safe choice.} 
