13. Bd2 {This quiet move is the other main try, and it requires a different answer than13.Re1when we play13...Bd5.} 
13. Nbc6 {This simple developing move is best.13...Bd5?as mentioned doesn't work this time:14.Neg5hxg515.Nxg5Ng616.Bxd5exd517.Qh3Re818.Qh7+Kf8and White gets a crushing attack with19.f4!In the same position with Re1 instead of Bd2 White didn't have time for the move 19. f4 because the rook was hanging on e1.Also we should be aware that13...Ng6?is to be avoided due to the simple tactic14.Nxd6!Qxd615.Bb4.13... Nbc6 just develops the knight, takes care of this latter threat, and asks White how he is going to continue.} 
14. Rfe1
14. Ng6 {Apart from pre-emptively blocking a checkmate threat on h7, we're also preparing ...Bf4 as we would like to exchange some pieces.} 
15. Rad1 {Stockfish finds a crazy line with15.Bxh6gxh616.Nxd6Qxd617.Rxe6when clearly we can't take with the pawn on e6. However, it turns out that the position after17...Qxe618.Bxe6Nf4!19.Qd2fxe6is quite comfortable for Black, who has two pieces and a rook versus a queen.} 
15. Bf4 {Intending to exchange on d2. White could avoid this with17.Bc3, but then17...Nce7followed by ...Nd5 would again question this bishop. All in all it's a perfectly fine IQP position for Black.} 
