[White "5) That Annoying 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3!? Line (and the KIA)"]
[Black "Chapter 5 Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3 {2.d3d53.Nd2g6As this is the line that 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 often transposes to, it'll receive most of our attention in this chapter.} 
2. d5
3. d3 {This is an annoying computerish line which I wanted to find a different answer for Black than going into the ending with3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1. After all, that's what White is expecting and is gunning for.} 
3. g6 {I think this is Black's best alternative to3...dxe4. Quite often at this point White will play4.Nbd2when play transposes into a King's Indian Attack against the Caro-Kann with ...g6. This is a valid alternate way of playing against the KIA.} 
4. e5 {The main attempt if White doesn't fancy transposing to a KIA.} 
4. c5 {Most high-rated games (admittedly most of them blitz and rapid games) saw Black continuing with the automatic4...Bg75.d4f6,when I haven't been able to find a path to equality for Black. Instead I think we should immediately prepare for White seizing the center with c3 and d4.} 
5. c3
5. Nc6
6. d4 {Opening buffs will recognize that we've actually transposed to a line of the Sicilian! Specifically, if Black plays the Accelerated Dragon (1.e4c52.Nf3g6) and then White responds with an Alapin setup (3.c3d54.e5Nc65.d4etc.). Personally I don't find this to be very testing for Black, although the computer likes White's position.} 
