1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. d3 {This is a weird little move which has become really popular since 2019. The main reason for its popularity being that the endgame that arises after3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1is assessed positively for White by the engine, and indeed it's quite easy for Black to go wrong! Still, if you're not afraid of that endgame as Black, go for it. However, if you don't want to play along with White, the following can be a good try as well.} 
3. g6 {We can delay the decision to take on e4, and offer White to transpose to a King's Indian Attack against the Caro - specifically, the line1.e4c62.d3d53.Nd2g6!?,which is perfectly playable for Black. There are only a couple of ways for White to avoid that transposition. 4. Nbd2 is a popular move here when play would indeed transpose directly.} 
4. Be2 {This is like a KIA but then with the bishop on e2 instead of g2, so White is playing in 'Old Indian' style.} 
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. e5 {We can play in the same way as I will recommend against the KIA - ...e5 and then ...Ne7.} 
6. Nbd2
6. Ne7
7. Re1 {White is faster with Re1 than in the KIA proper, but here he is not yet threatening to win a pawn on e5 because the e2-bishop is in the way.} 
7. O-O
8. Bf1 {The most straightforward continuation. Sometimes the move8.c3is seen, when I would propose8...c5followed by putting a knight on c6.} 
8. d4 {Just like in the King's Indian proper, this move is usually quite strong once the King's Indian player has put the rook on e1/e8. With the center closed, the rook is no longer doing anything on the e-file, and White will have to spend at least two more moves to put it back on f1.Next, Black should play ...c5 and put a knight on c6, then ...Be6 and an advance on the queenside makes good sense.} 
