[White "5) That Annoying 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3!? Line (and the KIA)"]
[Black "3.d3!? with 4.exd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. d3 {This is a weird little move which has become really popular since 2019. The main reason for its popularity being that the endgame that arises after3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1is assessed positively for White by the engine, and indeed it's quite easy for Black to go wrong! Still, if you're not afraid of that endgame as Black, go for it. However, if you don't want to play along with White, the following can be a good try as well.} 
3. g6 {We can delay the decision to take on e4, and offer White to transpose to a King's Indian Attack against the Caro - specifically, the line1.e4c62.d3d53.Nd2g6!?,which is perfectly playable for Black. There are only a couple of ways for White to avoid that transposition. 4. Nbd2 is a popular move here when play would indeed transpose directly.} 
4. exd5 {A rare move but it should be checked. However, multiple top GMs have had the position after 3... g6 with White and none of them have played 4. exd5, so it can't be that special.} 
4. cxd5
5. d4 {This is White's idea. Essentially, we have an exchange Caro-Kann (1.e4c62.d4d53.exd5cxd5) where Black has an extra tempo, but that tempo has been spent on the sub-optimal move ...g6. There are actually some lines in the Exchange Caro where Black voluntarily plays ...g6, but most of them are regarded as giving White a slight advantage, or at least are seen as worse for Black than the mainlines.I could write a dissertation about the Exchange Caro with ...g6, so I'll try to summarize what is going on. The main idea of ...g6 in such lines is actually not that Black wants to develop the bishop to g7. The bishop is usually not that great on g7, looking at White's pawn chain c3-d4  (though it's not super terrible either - it depends on how well White controls the e7-e5 break). Instead, the main point of playing ...g6 is that Black, in reply to Bd3, wants to offer the exchange of bishops with ...Bf5. A possible exchange Bxf5 gxf5 is not that bad for Black's pawn chain and would alleviate Black's space issue.A typical line that illustrates this is1.e4c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.Bd3Nc65.c3Qc76.h3Nf67.Nf3g68.Qc2(note how White is trying to prevent ...Bf5)8...Nh59.O-ONf410.Bb5Bg711.Re1Bf512.Qd2.Black managed to get the bishop to f5 but he will soon have to retreat some of his pieces, while White can more easily untangle and is thus better.} 
5. Nc6 {I would suggest to start by developing the knights and see where White puts the light-squared bishop, and whether he wants to waste a (nother) tempo on the move h2-h3.} 
6. c3
6. Nf6
7. Be2 {7.Bd3Bf5!is at least equal for Black for reasons explained on White's 5th move.} 
7. Bg7
8. O-O
8. O-O {Here White's setup is a bit too timid to achieve much.} 
9. Nbd2 {9.Bf4Ne410.Nbd2h6!?is likely to transpose to the line we'll see with 7. h3, with Black playing ...g5 and ...f5 next.} 
9. Bf5 {Only to this square.9...Bg410.h3Bxf311.Nxf3would just give up the bishop pair for nothing.} 
10. Re1 {In case of10.Nh4Bd7,the knight on h4 will have to retreat sooner or later, when we can put the bishop back on f5.} 
10. Qc7 {Black has a harmonious enough position. Next the rooks can come to d8 and e8, and we can toy with the idea of playing ...e5.For instance,11.Bf1Rfe8might tempt White into preventing ...e5 with12.Ne5?, but this loses at least a pawn after12...Nxe5and 13... Ng4 due to the threat on h2.} 
*
