6. c3
6. Nf6
7. h3 {This was seen in the only game to reach this exact position.} 
7. Bg7 {Rambaldi - Le Roux continued7...Qc78.g3!?Bg79.Bf4Qb6etc. I propose to just develop and not bother with trying to prevent White from playing Bf4.} 
8. Bf4
8. O-O {So far we're making straightforward moves.} 
9. Be2 {White's moves also make a lot of sense, but he is a bit behind in development. This can be seen after9. Bd3:9...Nd7!10.O-Oe5!11.dxe5Ndxe5and now e.g.12.Be2Nxf3+13.Bxf3Be6sees Black actually getting some advantage as the ...d4 advance is on the cards, which will open up Black's bishops while getting rid of the IQP.} 
9. Ne4 {Here9...Nd7and 10... e5 is less strong as Black doesn't gain a tempo on the d3-bishop. Instead I suggest exploiting White's lack of control over e4 by centralizing followed by advancing kingside pawns.} 
10. O-O
10. h6 {Preparing ...g5.} 
11. Nbd2
11. g5
12. Bh2
12. f5 {A bit commital, but I think it makes sense here. White is not well-placed to either play c4, which would be a natural way to fight against Black's position, or evict the e4-knight/make use of the e5-square. A nice plan for Black here is Be6-f7-h5.} 
