1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. d3 {This is a weird little move which has become really popular since 2019. The main reason for its popularity being that the endgame that arises after3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1is assessed positively for White by the engine, and indeed it's quite easy for Black to go wrong! Still, if you're not afraid of that endgame as Black, go for it. However, if you don't want to play along with White, the following can be a good try as well.} 
3. g6 {We can delay the decision to take on e4, and offer White to transpose to a King's Indian Attack against the Caro - specifically, the line1.e4c62.d3d53.Nd2g6!?,which is perfectly playable for Black. There are only a couple of ways for White to avoid that transposition. 4. Nbd2 is a popular move here when play would indeed transpose directly.} 
4. e5 {The main way to try to punish Black for combining a Caro-Kann with ...g6. However, if we compare this to the line1.e4c62.d4d53.Nd2g64.e5,which is regarded as better for White, Black will be a full tempo up here as White has played d2-d3 (and presumably will play d3-d4 sometime soon).} 
4. c5 {This seems the most accurate reply. Instead, most games have continued4...Bg75.d4f66.exf6Nxf6,when Black has scored well. However, these were mostly blitz and rapid games, and objectively it seems that White might get an advantage in this line if he plays accurately.After 4... c5, if White plays in the most challenging way, we actually get a transposition to a delayed Alapin versus the Accelerated Dragon. If you don't know what that refers to, I'm talking about the line1.e4c52.Nf3g6(Accelerated Dragon)3.c3!?(delayed Alapin)3...d54.e5Nc65.d4.Here, instead of 4. e5, the most played (and arguably more testing) move is4.exd5.Anyway, the main thing to understand about this line with 4. e5 is not to play ...Bg7 too early. The most likely structure to appear is one with White having pawns on d4 and e5, when the bishop would bite on granite from g7. Instead, we should anticipate a white pawn arriving on d4 with the moves ...c5, ...Nc6 and ...Bg4.} 
5. d4 {The immediate 5. d4 is a possibility to consider.} 
5. Nc6 {5...cxd4is a principled alternative, taking the pawn before White has the chance to play c2-c3. However, after6.Qxd4e67.Bg5White does get a quite large lead in development and has us block our light-squared bishop in. The computer thinks this is fine for Black, but your mileage may vary.} 
6. dxc5 {The only testing line here is White grabbing this pawn.6.c3Bg4would in fact just transpose to 5. c3.} 
6. Bg4 {Now we'd like to continue ...Bg7 and ...e6.} 
7. Bb5
7. Qa5+ {The only game in this position continued7...Rc8,but I think the queen check is more accurate. We force White to put a knight on c3, which means he can't play the desirable pawn move c2-c3.} 
8. Nc3
8. e6 {The d5-pawn was hanging.} 
9. O-O
9. Bg7 {9...Bxc5is not terrible, but will eventually run into a3, b4 or Na4 at some point. It's more to the point to focus on the e5-pawn instead.After9...Bg7White can't hold on to both pawns anyway:10.Qd4?!might be the best materialistic try, but10...Bxf311.gxf3Nge712.f4a6will see us soon regain the c5-pawn with a much better position to boot.} 
10. Bf4 {There are multiple moves for White, but Black's plan is mostly the same: ...a6, ... O-O and perhaps ...Nf5 and ...Bxf3 too if it works out well.} 
10. Nge7 {Black can afford to play slowly. Next is ...O-O. The issue is that if White really wants to hold on to the c5-pawn, he'll have to play a3 and b4. But this is terrible because it would open the diagonal for the bishop on g7.On the other hand, something like11.Re1a6!12.Bf1Qxc5is just great for Black. What exactly are White's pieces doing?} 
