[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) That Annoying 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3!? Line (and the KIA)"]
[Black "KIA with 5.d4!?"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d3
2. d5
3. Nd2 {This is how White plays the King's Indian Attack against the Caro-Kann, intending to continue with 4. Ngf3, 5. g3, 6. Bg2, and so on. Here play normally continues3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3Nf66.Bg2O-O7.O-Oetc., though White does have a tricky sideline in 5. d4!? that Black should know how to handle.However, there is a second popular way of playing for Black that also promises (at least) equal chances, starting with 3... g6!? - let's look at it here.} 
3. g6 {The idea is to fianchetto the bishop, then play ...e5 and then ...Ne7 and ...O-O. This way we avoid lines in the KIA where White pushes a pawn to e5 himself, which often happens in e.g. the KIA against the French.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. d4 {The only independent alternative that has seen some play here.} 
5. dxe4
6. Nxe4
6. Nf6 {This seems natural enough. Now White should take on f6, as7.Bd3Nxe48.Bxe4Nd7followed by ...e5 is very insipid for White.} 
7. Nxf6+
7. exf6 {If you know the 4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 line against the classical Caro-Kann, this move should come naturally to you. I won't give further moves, but just note that play is very similar to that line. Black's extra pawn on the kingside helps his king safety and allows him to move those pawns forward even without having to worry too much about his own king. White has an extra pawn on the queenside/in the center, but how is he going to create a passed pawn that is not a weakness?A good plan of development for Black is ...O-O, ...a5, ... Na6-c7, then put the light-squared bishop on e6 or f5.} 
