[White "5) That Annoying 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3!? Line (and the KIA)"]
[Black "KIA with 6.Qe2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d3
2. d5
3. Nd2 {This is how White plays the King's Indian Attack against the Caro-Kann, intending to continue with 4. Ngf3, 5. g3, 6. Bg2, and so on. Here play normally continues3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3Nf66.Bg2O-O7.O-Oetc., though White does have a tricky sideline in 5. d4!? that Black should know how to handle.However, there is a second popular way of playing for Black that also promises (at least) equal chances, starting with 3... g6!? - let's look at it here.} 
3. g6 {The idea is to fianchetto the bishop, then play ...e5 and then ...Ne7 and ...O-O. This way we avoid lines in the KIA where White pushes a pawn to e5 himself, which often happens in e.g. the KIA against the French.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. g3 {5.Be2is an alternative, but it would just transpose to a line we've seen via the move order 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 4. Be2 - see the variation.} 
5. e5 {This setup is the point. The knight will come to e7 after which Black can castle.} 
6. Qe2 {Though6.Bg2is the overwhelming main move, a few games have seen this queen move.} 
6. Ne7 {Most black players opted to play6...d4,as they probably thought that White threatens to take exd5 and then take the pawn on e5. But it's not actually a threat at all.} 
7. exd5 {White should revert to normal development with7.Bg2,but then his early Qe2 move didn't really have a point.} 
7. cxd5
8. Nxe5 {Again8.Bg2is better, but at this point Black would have a large advantage because of his central control.} 
8. O-O {With ...Re8 and the e7-knight moving soon, White is in huge trouble.} 
