[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d3
2. d5
3. Nd2 {This is how White plays the King's Indian Attack against the Caro-Kann, intending to continue with 4. Ngf3, 5. g3, 6. Bg2, and so on. Here play normally continues3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3Nf66.Bg2O-O7.O-Oetc., though White does have a tricky sideline in 5. d4!? that Black should know how to handle.However, there is a second popular way of playing for Black that also promises (at least) equal chances, starting with 3... g6!? - let's look at it here.} 
3. g6 {The idea is to fianchetto the bishop, then play ...e5 and then ...Ne7 and ...O-O. This way we avoid lines in the KIA where White pushes a pawn to e5 himself, which often happens in e.g. the KIA against the French.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. g3 {5.Be2is an alternative, but it would just transpose to a line we've seen via the move order 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 4. Be2 - see the variation.} 
5. e5 {This setup is the point. The knight will come to e7 after which Black can castle.} 
6. Bg2
6. Ne7
7. O-O {Both sides just making the standard moves.} 
7. O-O {The starting position for the KIA Caro with ...g6. Now White has to decide which plan to follow. The main move is clearly8.Re1, but other moves which have seen play (in order of ascending popularity) are8.a4,8.b3,8.Qe2,8.c3and8.b4.There have been a couple of hundred games with this position, but I don't think it makes sense to study a huge amount of theory here as KIA players don't play their opening to get a theoretical advantage, they just want an interesting game. So we'll only look at a couple of typical ideas.} 
8. b3 {White intends to develop the bishop to b2, but I'm not sure if that's such a good idea.} 
8. a5 {We grab some space and toy with the idea of playing ...a4.} 
9. Bb2 {9.a4can be answered by9...Na610.Bb2d4,when Black can continue with ...c5 and put the other knight on c6 while the a6-knight could go to b4.} 
9. d4 {I think it makes sense to blunt White's bishop. Was it really worth playing b3 and Bb2 just to have the bishop made useless?} 
10. c3 {The immediate10.Nc4runs into10...b5!- A theme we will also see after 8. Re1.} 
10. c5 {Black has more space. It depends on whether White will exchange soon on d4 or not, but if he does, a good developing scheme for Black is Nec6 and put the other knight on c5.} 
