2. d5
3. Nd2 {This is how White plays the King's Indian Attack against the Caro-Kann, intending to continue with 4. Ngf3, 5. g3, 6. Bg2, and so on. Here play normally continues3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3Nf66.Bg2O-O7.O-Oetc., though White does have a tricky sideline in 5. d4!? that Black should know how to handle.However, there is a second popular way of playing for Black that also promises (at least) equal chances, starting with 3... g6!? - let's look at it here.} 
3. g6 {The idea is to fianchetto the bishop, then play ...e5 and then ...Ne7 and ...O-O. This way we avoid lines in the KIA where White pushes a pawn to e5 himself, which often happens in e.g. the KIA against the French.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. g3 {5.Be2is an alternative, but it would just transpose to a line we've seen via the move order 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 4. Be2 - see the variation.} 
5. e5 {This setup is the point. The knight will come to e7 after which Black can castle.} 
6. Bg2
6. Ne7
7. O-O {Both sides just making the standard moves.} 
7. O-O {The starting position for the KIA Caro with ...g6. Now White has to decide which plan to follow. The main move is clearly8.Re1, but other moves which have seen play (in order of ascending popularity) are8.a4,8.b3,8.Qe2,8.c3and8.b4.There have been a couple of hundred games with this position, but I don't think it makes sense to study a huge amount of theory here as KIA players don't play their opening to get a theoretical advantage, they just want an interesting game. So we'll only look at a couple of typical ideas.} 
8. Re1 {Clearly the main move. White is now threatening to win the pawn on e5.} 
8. d4 {There are other possible moves, but I think this is thematic. Now the rook looks silly on e1 and White will have to lose some time bringing it back to f1.} 
9. Nc4 {This is the most played move, which is actually a bit shocking as it's a clear mistake. White should first play9.a4, when a good continuation for Black is9...c5and 10... Nbc6 followed by developing the c8-bishop with a typical position.After 9. Nc4 it might seem like White is developing with a tempo on the e5-pawn, but...} 
9. b5 {But after this move he has to go back and is actually losing time. The point is that after10.Ncxe5f6the knight is trapped. Actually the computer wants White to go for this line, with the following continuation:11.Nxg6!?Nxg612.c3(introducing ideas with Qb3+, and the d4-pawn is hard to hold on to for Black)12...c513.cxd4cxd414.Nxd4!?Qxd415.e5(the point; White regains some material)15...Nxe5!16.Bxa8Bg4and Black has a very strong initiative with roughly equal material.} 
10. Ncd2
10. a5 {If allowed we'll play 11... a4 next, when we can do whatever we want on the queenside, so White should take action immediately.} 
11. a4 {The computer wants to play11.c3, sacrificing a pawn with11...dxc312.bxc3Qxd3, and then offer to trade queens with13.Nb3. Needless to say, this can't be challenging for Black.} 
11. Nd7 {One advantage of having the pawn on c6 is that we don't have to answer White's a4 with ...b4, which would fix the pawn structure in White's favor. Now our idea is to play ...Nb6 next, asking White a question about the pawn on a4.} 
12. b3 {Perhaps this is White's best try.} 
12. Nb6
13. Ba3 {This is the point. Now13...bxa4?!14.bxa4would render the a3-bishop quite useful, as it's preventing us from playing ... c5-c4, while we can't grab the a4-pawn.} 
13. b4 {We don't need to be afraid to close the queenside.} 
14. Bc1
14. c5 {Now we'll just prepare the ... f5 advance. To achieve that, first we should vacate the h1-a8 diagonal. White is far too slow to play f2-f4 himself.} 
15. h3 {For instance,15.Rf1Ra716.Nh4f5!and Black is first.Only15.Nh4Ra716.f4?sees White beat us in the race to be the first to move the f-pawn, but then16...exf417.gxf4f5!is really great for Black, who is threatening to play ...fxe4 when White has no good answer - the f4-pawn hangs, dxe4 would allow ...d3 and the a1-h8 diagonal is opened, and retaking on e4 with a piece would allow Black to play a knight to d5 and then c3 or e3.} 
15. Ra7
16. Nf1 {If White plays this move prematurely, Black even gets a nice extra resource.} 
16. c4 {A very nice pawn sac.} 
17. dxc4 {17.bxc4?Bd7just allows Black to pick off the a4-pawn.} 
17. Nd7 {The knight is coming to c5, after which Black is ready to continue with ...f5 and ...e4. White is struggling to avoid a lost position.} 
