[White "6) Fantasy Variation With 3...g6"]
[Black "Chapter 6 Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. f3
3. g6 {Black's third most common move after3...e6and3...dxe4is the fianchetto. I was also thinking of creating a chapter based on3...e6, but this has been analyzed in both Rambaldi's recent repertoire book as well as the book by Johnsen & Hansen, and I probably wouldn't have a lot of original analysis to add to those two books.} 
4. Nc3
4. Bg7
5. Be3 {This is how the vast majority of games continue.5.e5!is actually the critical test after which I've been unable to find an equalizer for Black. White has to be super booked up to realize this, though.5...f6is my main recommendation, trying to make use of the fact that we've already put the bishop on g7. Play probably continues6.f4Nh67.Nf3Bg48.Be2O-Oand so on - Black gets decent squares for most of the pieces, but White has a space advantage and the bishop on g7 remains a bit silly.I also analyze the alternative5...h5,which is pretty good for Black if White doesn't really know what is happening, but can be dangerous for Black if White plays very purposefully.} 
5. Qb6 {Now there is a double idea - either take the b2-pawn or make use of the pin on the d4-pawn, and White can't deal with both at the same time.} 
6. Qd2 {We'll look at all the alternatives here as well. The main one seems to be6.Rb1when6...dxe47.fxe4e5followed by ...exd4 gives Black good play.} 
6. Qxb2
7. Rb1
7. Qa3 {Now White again has a choice. The most common response is 8. exd5 which regains the pawn.} 
8. exd5
8. Nf6
9. dxc6
9. bxc6 {Almost all games here have continued with9...bxc6, but I will analyze9...Nxc6as well as it makes sense to develop the knight. In any case, though, Black has scored very well from the position after 9. dxc6, which should be evaluated as around equal to slightly better for Black.} 
