[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Fantasy Variation With 3...g6"]
[Black "Fantasy 3...g6 4. e5?!"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. f3 {A course dealing with White's sidelines against the Caro-Kann can't skip over the Fantasy variation, which is a unique line in that Black won't be able to get a 'typical' Caro pawn structure most of the time.} 
3. g6 {Most recent books focus on the usual continuation3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg4, which has accumulated quite some theory. I feel like this is playing a bit into White's hands though, as this is the kind of game & pawn structure White is looking for when playing 3. f3.Keep it Simple for Black gave3...Qb6, which is a quirky and good alternative with not much theory.3...e6is the other main line which still seems fully valid. However, it was recently examined in the book Win with the Caro-Kann by Sverre Johnsen & Torbjorn Hansen (2021). They gave some fun new ideas for Black and I don't want to just copy their analysis, so I went with3...g6instead.The downside of 3... g6 is that, if White 100% knows what they are doing, it won't equalize. The upside is that 99.9% of the time White doesn't play that way.} 
4. e5 {I wasn't going to cover this move, but Wesley So played it against Awonder Liang in the 2020 US rapid championship, and a few other grandmasters have essayed it as well. This is not the right moment for this advance, though.} 
4. c5 {Liang's move, which was right on the money. We should treat the position like a Caro-Kann advance where both sides have made an extra pawn move. The move g7-g6 is mostly irrelevant, but the move f2-f3 for White makes his position a lot worse. In many variations of the 3... c5 Advance Caro-Kann, White relies on being able to put a knight on f3.} 
5. dxc5
5. e6 {Here we see a case in point. Compared to the Advance 3... c5 line, here White can't play any of the lines involving Nf3 or Qg4, which severely limits his choice.} 
6. Be3 {In the adjacent position with the pawns back on f2 and g7 this is the traditional mainline, trying to hold on to White's extra pawn. Here it's the only testing possibility.} 
6. Nd7
7. Bb5
7. Qc7 {Liang's move, which already regains a pawn. In the Advance Caro line this is not such a great move because of8.b4Qxe59.Nd2followed by 10. Ngf3, which provides White with a strong initiative. Here8.b4?!Qxe5already gives White some trouble because both the rook on a1 and the bishop on e3 are hanging.In the game Liang soon was actually a pawn up, although he eventually lost the game. Definitely he won the opening battle, though.} 
