[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. f3 {A course dealing with White's sidelines against the Caro-Kann can't skip over the Fantasy variation, which is a unique line in that Black won't be able to get a 'typical' Caro pawn structure most of the time.} 
3. g6 {Most recent books focus on the usual continuation3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg4, which has accumulated quite some theory. I feel like this is playing a bit into White's hands though, as this is the kind of game & pawn structure White is looking for when playing 3. f3.Keep it Simple for Black gave3...Qb6, which is a quirky and good alternative with not much theory.3...e6is the other main line which still seems fully valid. However, it was recently examined in the book Win with the Caro-Kann by Sverre Johnsen & Torbjorn Hansen (2021). They gave some fun new ideas for Black and I don't want to just copy their analysis, so I went with3...g6instead.The downside of 3... g6 is that, if White 100% knows what they are doing, it won't equalize. The upside is that 99.9% of the time White doesn't play that way.} 
4. Be3
4. Bg7 {Now White will usually play5.Nc3when play transposes back to 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Be3 - see here for coverage.} 
5. c3 {This has been played by a couple of grandmasters such as Mickey Adams, but it looks very artificial to me.} 
5. e5 {I think this is best. Another good line is5...dxe46.fxe4Nf6, intending to harass White's bishop after7.Nd2Ng48.Bg5h6etc.With 5... e5 we just claim our share of the center and want to make sure that White can't play e4-e5 any longer after we move our g8-knight out.Also, concretely we create a threat:6.--exd47.cxd4dxe4and White can't recapture on e4 due to ...Qh4+.White might play7.Bxd4because of that, but after7...Nf6we have a great position.} 
6. dxe5 {Because ...exd4 is not really palatable, this is what White might play.} 
6. Bxe5
7. exd5 {Now it's not bad to retake on d5, but Stockfish wants to play a fun little gambit.} 
7. Nf6
8. dxc6
8. Qe7 {That's the point. Obviously we weren't going to exchange queens.} 
9. cxb7
9. Bxb7 {With great compensation for the two pawns. Concretely we want to play ...O-O, ...Re8 and ...Nd5 and destroy White on the e-file.According to the computer, White's best line continues10.Bb5+Bc6!11.Bxc6+Nxc612.Ne2O-O13.O-Owhen13...Bxh2+already regains one of the pawns with an ongoing initiative.} 
