1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. f3 {A course dealing with White's sidelines against the Caro-Kann can't skip over the Fantasy variation, which is a unique line in that Black won't be able to get a 'typical' Caro pawn structure most of the time.} 
3. g6 {Most recent books focus on the usual continuation3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg4, which has accumulated quite some theory. I feel like this is playing a bit into White's hands though, as this is the kind of game & pawn structure White is looking for when playing 3. f3.Keep it Simple for Black gave3...Qb6, which is a quirky and good alternative with not much theory.3...e6is the other main line which still seems fully valid. However, it was recently examined in the book Win with the Caro-Kann by Sverre Johnsen & Torbjorn Hansen (2021). They gave some fun new ideas for Black and I don't want to just copy their analysis, so I went with3...g6instead.The downside of 3... g6 is that, if White 100% knows what they are doing, it won't equalize. The upside is that 99.9% of the time White doesn't play that way.} 
4. Nc3 {White's standard move, not yet committing to a central setup.} 
4. Bg7
5. e5 {This is a rare move, but definitely the strongest. Compared to the situation after 4. e5?! c5 our bishop on g7 is now clearly misplaced and we won't get in ...c5 so easily.} 
5. h5 {Let me go on a little tangent here because we're almost transposing to a different opening: in the Modern1.e4g62.d4d6there is the weird little line3.Nc3c6!?4.f4d55.e5h5.In our current position in the Caro-Kann line, if White now plays6.f4, we could even play6...Bf8and have the exact same position (there are more useful moves than putting the bishop back on f8, though, even if it ultimately belongs there).In our current position, the point is that White should NOT play 6. f4, because it makes it a lot easier for Black to occupy the light squares on the kingside. The pawn being on f3 is actually very annoying for Black if we're playing with ...h5! Hence I would only play like this (5... h5) if you suspect your opponent might not be aware of such details and will naively answer 6. f4. My main suggestion5...f6is more solid, even though it will end up giving White a slight edge.} 
6. Bf4 {Alex Banzea's recommendation in Ambush 1.e4, and this is the problem with ...h5. White is not obliged to move the pawn from f3 to f4 and can keep it on f3 to deny us the g4-square.The problem is that we're running out of useful moves. We could play6...Nh6and delay the decision of how to deal with the c8-bishop, but what then after7.Qd2?Obviously playing ...e6 before moving out the bishop would be an admission of failure (not to mention a large advantage for White), but moving it to f5 now is very dangerous. Still, it's probably what Black should try. Banzea gives some other tries for Black, for example the maneuver Nd7-f8-e6, but all of them seem very artificial to me, and easy to refute with an engine.} 
6. Bf5 {As explained, this seems the most logical, but it's also very risky.} 
7. Qd2 {We should hope for something like7.g4?!Be6!when White can't move the queen without dropping the pawn on g4, while we would obviously love to see it either go forward to g5 or exchange itself on h5.} 
7. e6 {Now we constantly have to be aware of White's attempts to trap our bishop with g2-g4.} 
8. Nge2
8. Nd7 {A generally useful developing move. Depending on how White continues we could next play ...c5, or e.g.9.O-O-Ob5!?when the knight could come to b6.} 
9. Rg1 {Slowly but methodically preparing g2-g4. It's not immediately a threat yet because we have a queen check on h4, but White will get there eventually. For instance, White could play 10. g3, 11. h3 and 12. g4.} 
9. Bh6 {I've checked almost every legal move in this position, and I think this is probably Black's best answer. We're not actually intending to exchange dark-squared bishops, but rather we prepare the move ...g6-g5, altering the kingside pawn configuration. And we wouldn't mind the exchange10.Bxh6?Nxh6when suddenly we're quite well organized and 11... f6 is on the cards, which means White would have to abandon the attempts to slowly trap our bishop by playing g4.} 
10. O-O-O {The only way the computer thinks White can maintain the advantage. 11. g4 is now a concrete threat (remember that it wasn't on the previous move because, with the king on e1, we have a check on h4).} 
10. g5
11. Be3 {Now we at least won't get the f5-bishop trapped! White has a new threat, though, or rather the same threat but with a different idea:11...--12.g4hxg413.fxg4Bg6and now14.h4!gxh415.g5Bf816.Nf4is very good for White positionally. So we still need to prevent White from playing g2-g4!} 
11. g4 {Physically preventing g2-g4. Our pawns on the kingside end up being quite vulnerable though.} 
12. Nf4 {Only like this.12.Bxh6Nxh613.Nf4Qg5!and it's not that bad for Black anymore.Or12.Kb1Bxe313.Qxe3Ne7and Black should be able to consolidate with a queen move, ...a6 and long castling.} 
12. Qc7
13. Be2 {Clearly not13.Nxh5??Bxe3and White loses the knight. After13.Be2!White is threatening--14.Nxh5though, as now at the end of the line14...Bxe315.Qxe3Rxh5White has16.fxg4with a fork.} 
13. O-O-O {I'm cutting the line here as I think it's unlikely that a white player, even if they prepared to play the line 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e5! h5 6. Bf4, will get exactly this position. It could continue as follows:14.Nxh5Bxe315.Qxe3Bxc216.Kxc2Rxh517.Rh1gxf318.Qxf3Rf519.Qh3f6.White keeps some advantage here but it should be manageable for Black.If you don't like how this looks, I suggest you play the line 5... f6 instead, which is more straightforward to play for both players and should lead to a smaller edge for White if both sides play correctly.} 
