11. fxe5 {Now White has a choice of recaptures.} 
12. dxe5 {White should not allow the trade of rooks. This significantly changes the pawn structure in the center, though.} 
12. Qb6+ {We should not allow White to consolidate his control over the dark squares by playing Be3.} 
13. Nd4 {13.Kh1?is a blunder due to13...Bxe5, while13.Qd4loses time after13...c5!14.Qd1Nc6.} 
13. g5 {I wanted to show this idea because it will no doubt throw your opponent for a loop. Both13...c5and13...Nf5are decent solid alternatives, but White keeps some small pull there because of his space advantage and because the g7-bishop is quite bad.13...g5is the critical move, attacking White's central pawn chain at its base, and White's best move is far from obvious.First,14.fxg5?!will inevitably lead to the fall of the e5-pawn:14...Nf5!15.Nef3Nxd416.Nxd4Rxf1+17.Kxf1c518.Nf3Nc619.Qe2Rf820.Kg1Nxe5!21.Nxe5c4+22.Kh1Bxe5etc. - You don't have to memorize this, but you can see how all the moves come naturally for Black.Then, there's14.g3?!, which is bad for a different reason. after14...gxf415.gxf4c516.Ndf3Nf5suddenly we have a great knight on f5, and a good plan to activate our bad bishop: ...Kh8, ...Rg8 and ...Bh6. Only Black can be for choice in that situation.White's best move is14.a4!First, we can't allow a4-a5, so we should reply14...a5.But that means that once we play ... c5, White's knight can settle on the b5-square. Also, after ...gxf4 gxf4 now White can swing over a rook with Ra3-h3. This means that after15.g3Nf516.c3or15...gxf416.gxf4c517.Nb5White keeps a small advantage.In the end, this line is why 3...g6 does not equalize, but it's a rare guest and even many (most?) grandmasters don't seem to be aware of 5.e5! etc. - so don't let that discourage you!} 
