[White "6) Fantasy Variation With 3...g6"]
[Black "Fantasy 3...g6 with 5. Be3, 6. a3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. f3 {A course dealing with White's sidelines against the Caro-Kann can't skip over the Fantasy variation, which is a unique line in that Black won't be able to get a 'typical' Caro pawn structure most of the time.} 
3. g6 {Most recent books focus on the usual continuation3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg4, which has accumulated quite some theory. I feel like this is playing a bit into White's hands though, as this is the kind of game & pawn structure White is looking for when playing 3. f3.Keep it Simple for Black gave3...Qb6, which is a quirky and good alternative with not much theory.3...e6is the other main line which still seems fully valid. However, it was recently examined in the book Win with the Caro-Kann by Sverre Johnsen & Torbjorn Hansen (2021). They gave some fun new ideas for Black and I don't want to just copy their analysis, so I went with3...g6instead.The downside of 3... g6 is that, if White 100% knows what they are doing, it won't equalize. The upside is that 99.9% of the time White doesn't play that way.} 
4. Nc3 {White's standard move, not yet committing to a central setup.} 
4. Bg7
5. Be3 {By far the main move, but Black is able to equalize after this.} 
5. Qb6 {This is key - otherwise Black just has a space disadvantage and nothing to show for it. We now get comparable positions to the line3.f3Qb6,but with our bishop being fianchettoed instead. However, the concept is similar - we're looking to play a combination of the moves ...e5 and ...dxe4. Meanwhile White has to attend the b2-pawn or find a good way to sacrifice it.White has tried a wide range of moves here, so let's check them one by one.} 
6. a3 {This counters the idea6...Qxb2, as now7.Na4would trap our queen, but it doesn't address the other idea we had with 5... Qb6.} 
6. e5
7. Nge2 {7.Na4doesn't help White. After7...Qa5+8.Nc3we don't have to repeat but can continue8...dxe49.fxe4Nf6with an active position.7.exd5?!exd48.Bf2does not lose material for White, but his position is quite awkward after8...Ne7.} 
7. Ne7 {Defending the d5-pawn while letting our g7-bishop keep an eye on e5 and d4.} 
8. Qd2 {The only way for White to untangle at some point. Now 9. dxe5 is an idea.} 
8. Qxb2 {We need to take the opportunity to grab this pawn. Otherwise White will castle long with an overwhelming position.} 
9. Ra2 {Other rook moves drop the a3-pawn.} 
9. Qb6
10. dxe5 {All of this is forced after 8. Qd2, and now we also see why we developed the knight to e7 instead of f6. At this point we have a choice of where to put our queen.} 
10. Qd8 {This was the choice of the only GM who had this position as Black, Dragan Solak. Three other players put the queen on a5 instead, which is also a valid choice - though in that case Black has to watch out for tactics involving moving the c3-knight away.} 
11. f4
11. O-O {At this point White has several ways to continue, so I'm cutting the line here.12.h4is Stockfish's suggestion, which should probably be answered by12...h5and 13... Bg4.12.Ng3seems like the human move, when12...Bh6!?is a tricky answer, intending13.Be2?d4!14.Bxd4Bxf4!White should probably insert13.exd5, but13...cxd5gives us a nice square on c6 for our b8-knight. Black can't be worse in that position.} 
