4. Nc3 {White's standard move, not yet committing to a central setup.} 
4. Bg7
5. Be3 {By far the main move, but Black is able to equalize after this.} 
5. Qb6 {This is key - otherwise Black just has a space disadvantage and nothing to show for it. We now get comparable positions to the line3.f3Qb6,but with our bishop being fianchettoed instead. However, the concept is similar - we're looking to play a combination of the moves ...e5 and ...dxe4. Meanwhile White has to attend the b2-pawn or find a good way to sacrifice it.White has tried a wide range of moves here, so let's check them one by one.} 
6. Na4
6. Qa5+
7. c3 {Usually White plays 7. c3. If they continue7.Nc3instead in order to make a quick draw, you can oblige with7...Qb6, but you can also play on with7...dxe48.fxe4c5!?intending9.dxc5Bxc3+.} 
7. e5 {This was only played once out of 45 games or so, but I think we should go for this move whenever it is possible. The main move is7...Nd7, but the problem I have with that is that White can grab a LOT of space with8.b4Qc79.e5f610.f4.} 
8. b4 {This seems like a plausible try. Otherwise White has to continually worry about the a4-knight being trapped.} 
8. Qc7 {Now the position normalizes a bit, as both sides have claimed their share of the center and the skirmish with the queen are over.} 
9. Bd3 {Note9.exd5Ne7!again - we love sacrificing that d5-pawn.} 
9. Ne7
10. Ne2
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. Nd7 {We can finish our development with ...b6 and ...Bb7, and ...Re8 can be tossed in as well. The position seems about equal.} 
