4. Bg7
5. Be3 {By far the main move, but Black is able to equalize after this.} 
5. Qb6 {This is key - otherwise Black just has a space disadvantage and nothing to show for it. We now get comparable positions to the line3.f3Qb6,but with our bishop being fianchettoed instead. However, the concept is similar - we're looking to play a combination of the moves ...e5 and ...dxe4. Meanwhile White has to attend the b2-pawn or find a good way to sacrifice it.White has tried a wide range of moves here, so let's check them one by one.} 
6. Rb1 {The second most popular move. Again, the issue is that this move addresses one of Black's ideas (attacking the b2-pawn) but not the other.} 
6. dxe4 {Here this is stronger than the immediate6...e5. The latter runs into7.Nge2Ne78.Qd2when the threat of dxe5 forces us to move our queen or take on d4, which we don't want to do there.} 
7. fxe4
7. e5
8. Nf3
8. exd4 {Again,8...Ne7?!9.Qd2!is awkward for Black.} 
9. Nxd4 {White should probably not exchange bishops for now. For instance, after9.Bxd4Bxd410.Nxd4Nf611.Be2O-OWhite can't castle due to12.O-O?Rd8and the d4-knight is lost.After 9. Nxd4 White is threatening 10. Nf5, so we have to move the queen somewhere.} 
9. Qb4 {Most games continued9...Qc7,but b4 seems a better square as now White can't develop actively with 10. Bc4.} 
10. a3
10. Qe7
11. Bc4
11. Nf6
12. O-O
12. O-O {White is quite active but the e4-pawn and e5-square are weaknesses that Black can try to exploit. What is important is that White has no good forward squares to jump to with his knights. 13... Nbd7 and 14... Ne5 is an idea, but 13... Ng4 and 14... Ne5 is also possible.} 
