8. Bd3 {If White wants to play for compensation, this solid developing move is probably the way to go.} 
8. dxe4 {I want to clarify the situation with ...dxe4 followed by ...e5 before continuing our development. The reason is that otherwise White might favorably close the center with e4-e5 at some point.} 
9. fxe4
9. e5
10. Nf3
10. exd4 {All of this is fairly natural.} 
11. Nxd4 {The computer actually prefers11.Bxd4Bxd412.Nxd4, but I find it hard to imagine any white player would go for that, weakening those dark squares and exchanging the good bishop.} 
11. Qe7 {An important moment. We should start with this move, moving our queen back to safety and keeping White's e-pawn in check.11...Nf6?is bad after12.e5Ng413.Ndb5!cxb514.Nxb5with a crushing attack for White.11...Ne7?12.Ncb5!is similar.} 
12. O-O
12. Nf6 {We're ready to castle and follow up with ...Nbd7-e5, when White still has to show compensation for the pawn.I should notify you that Stockfish gives the following violent variation here:13.e5Qxe514.Rxf6Qxf615.Ne4Qe716.Bg5!?Bxd4+17.Kh1Qe618.Bc4Qxe419.Re1Qxe1+20.Qxe1+Be6, and now after sacrificing a few pawns, an exchange and several pieces, White can perhaps keep the balance if he finds21.Qb4!c522.Qxb7O-O23.Bxe6fxe624.h3. That's the worst White can throw at Black, and Black is still on the right side of equality.} 
