3. g6 {Most recent books focus on the usual continuation3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg4, which has accumulated quite some theory. I feel like this is playing a bit into White's hands though, as this is the kind of game & pawn structure White is looking for when playing 3. f3.Keep it Simple for Black gave3...Qb6, which is a quirky and good alternative with not much theory.3...e6is the other main line which still seems fully valid. However, it was recently examined in the book Win with the Caro-Kann by Sverre Johnsen & Torbjorn Hansen (2021). They gave some fun new ideas for Black and I don't want to just copy their analysis, so I went with3...g6instead.The downside of 3... g6 is that, if White 100% knows what they are doing, it won't equalize. The upside is that 99.9% of the time White doesn't play that way.} 
4. Nc3 {White's standard move, not yet committing to a central setup.} 
4. Bg7
5. Be3 {By far the main move, but Black is able to equalize after this.} 
5. Qb6 {This is key - otherwise Black just has a space disadvantage and nothing to show for it. We now get comparable positions to the line3.f3Qb6,but with our bishop being fianchettoed instead. However, the concept is similar - we're looking to play a combination of the moves ...e5 and ...dxe4. Meanwhile White has to attend the b2-pawn or find a good way to sacrifice it.White has tried a wide range of moves here, so let's check them one by one.} 
6. Qd2 {Finally we get to the main move. White unpins the d4-pawn but ignores the threat to b2, so we should take on b2.} 
6. Qxb2
7. Rb1
7. Qa3 {At this point White has a choice to make.} 
8. exd5 {The main move, which is straightforward. White regains the sacrificed pawn. However, I should mention that Stockfish already thinks Black has a slight advantage after this move.} 
8. Nf6 {Developing with tempo.} 
9. dxc6 {White can at any time play9.Rb3in between, but it doesn't have much independent value. We always reply9...Qa5.} 
9. bxc6 {This is the move that is played almost all the time, though I haven't been able to find out why. Still, it is not bad and scores well for Black. One advantage of retaking with the pawn is that, regardless of where White now develops the f1-bishop, we can continue by exchanging it off with ...Ba6.} 
10. Bc4
10. Ba6
11. Rb3
11. Qa5
12. Bxa6
12. Nxa6 {12...Qxa6is also possible, but I like our queen on a5. The knight can go via c7 to d5, or perhaps support the ...c5 advance - e.g. if White plays12...Nxa613.Bh6?!Bxh614.Qxh6c5!.} 
13. Nge2
13. O-O
14. O-O
14. Rfd8 {Next Nc7-d5 is an idea, but Black can even consider playing ...Nc5!? and ...Ne6 next, if White doesn't step out of the pin on the d-file.} 
