4. Nc3 {White's standard move, not yet committing to a central setup.} 
4. Bg7
5. Be3 {By far the main move, but Black is able to equalize after this.} 
5. Qb6 {This is key - otherwise Black just has a space disadvantage and nothing to show for it. We now get comparable positions to the line3.f3Qb6,but with our bishop being fianchettoed instead. However, the concept is similar - we're looking to play a combination of the moves ...e5 and ...dxe4. Meanwhile White has to attend the b2-pawn or find a good way to sacrifice it.White has tried a wide range of moves here, so let's check them one by one.} 
6. Qd2 {Finally we get to the main move. White unpins the d4-pawn but ignores the threat to b2, so we should take on b2.} 
6. Qxb2
7. Rb1
7. Qa3 {At this point White has a choice to make.} 
8. exd5 {The main move, which is straightforward. White regains the sacrificed pawn. However, I should mention that Stockfish already thinks Black has a slight advantage after this move.} 
8. Nf6 {Developing with tempo.} 
9. dxc6 {White can at any time play9.Rb3in between, but it doesn't have much independent value. We always reply9...Qa5.} 
9. Nxc6
10. Bc4 {10.Nb5?doesn't help White, as after10...Qxa2the rook on b1 is hanging, and11.Rb3allows Black to cover the c7-square with11...Nd5.} 
10. O-O
11. Nge2
11. b6 {Black has a nice choice in this position.11...Rd8is also very good, for example, but I like playing in the same style as in the 9... bxc6 line. Exchanging light-squared bishops makes good positional sense, and White can't make use of our queen's position on a3.} 
12. O-O {12.Nb5Qa5is great for Black. We don't mind the exchange of queens at all.} 
12. Ba6
13. Nb5 {It's hard to suggest something better for White. If the bishop retreats to b3, for instance, then after13.Bb3Rac8and ...Rfd8 White faces enormous pressure on the c- and d-files.} 
13. Qa4 {This is a precise continuation. If you don't want to have to play accurately, then13...Bxb514.Bxb5Na5is a very simple alternative. It gives up the bishop pair, but Black retains great play against White's center.With 13... Qa4 things are a bit more complicated. There are some pins and tactics, but the upside is that Black keeps firm control over the position without giving up the bishop pair.} 
14. Bd3
14. Nd5 {With a threat of taking on e3, taking on b5 and taking the d4-pawn.} 
15. Bh6 {A line like15.c4Nxe316.Qxe3Bxb5!17.Rxb5Rad818.d5Ne5is also atrocious for White.} 
15. Na5 {Clamping down on the c4-square. We intend to continue with ...Nc4, perhaps prepared by ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8. Black has some advantage.} 
