[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Advance with 3...Bf5: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5 {From this position, of course, White has a huge amount of possibilities, almost too many to list. In this chapter I will only go through the following variations:A) The good:4.Nc3e65.g4Bg66.Nge2- here my recommendation is6...Ne7!?, an old pet line of mine which holds up well objectively, often leads White players to already make an error on the next move, and contains a lot less theory than the main move 6... c5;B) The bad:4.Nf3e65.Be2- the mainline of which continues5...c56.Be3Qb67.Nc3Nc68.O-OQxb29.Qe1, and now I've examined9...c4!?Objectively this is not such a good move, but the positions are so complicated and rich that it's very easy for White to lose their way;C) The ugly:4.h4h55.Bd3and now the odd-looking5...Qd7?!- looks very unnatural,  but I found it hard to prove more than a small advantage for White with best play, and it's not easy to form a good plan against.The variations 4. Nf3 and 4. h4 are still quite trendy nowadays, while the line 4. Nc3 e6 5. g4 was the mainline for much of the 90s and early 2000s, but has fallen into obscurity since. You'll still come across it occasionally, and there's even a Chessable course advocating it.My impression is that both 4. Nf3 and 4. h4 are still played a lot, but the line 4. h4 is perhaps the most popular nowadays, whereas the popularity of 4. Nf3 is drying up a bit as it has been analyzed to dust. Indeed, the line 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 is also very popular on Chessable, with multiple courses (multiple LTRs even!) advocating it.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Advance with 3...Bf5: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly"]
[Black "4. Nc3 Shirov Attack with 6... Ne7!? #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. Nc3 {As mentioned, this used to be the mainline some 20 years ago. I have fond memories of this variation, spending many hours studying the ideas, as one of the members of the local chess club would always play it against me.The idea of 4. Nc3, apart from that it develops the knight, is quite crude - White waits for Black to play ...e6 (which he inevitably has to play sooner or later) and the knight takes away the e4-square, so that White can start chasing the bishop with g4 and h4 next.} 
4. e6 {Black should oblige as the resulting positions are fine for him, even if it can become crazy complicated.} 
5. g4
5. Bg6
6. Nge2 {This move is White's idea - the knight is coming to f4 to further harass the bishop on g6. The immediate6.h4?doesn't make sense as Black can oppose this pawn with6...h5!,when g4 sticks out as a sore thumb.After6.Nge2Black has an interesting choice to make. The mainline was and still is6...c5, and you can find this in Erwin L'Ami's LTR. Black is completely fine in that line, though play remains incredibly sharp and tactical.} 
6. Ne7 {This used to be my pet line against 4. Nc3. It's a fully valid alternative to 6... c5, with less theory and (arguably) less sharp resulting positions, though the positions are still very tactical.I've also dabbled in6...f6from time to time, but the verdict nowadays seems to be that Black doesn't fully equalize there, e.g. in the variation7.h4!fxe58.h5!Bf79.dxe5.The idea behind6...Ne7is that Black first reinforces the bishop on g6 before deciding on further action. One problem with6...c5is that after7.h4h58.Nf4Black faces an issue with the h5-pawn (to be fair, nowadays we understand that Black can perfectly well sacrifice that pawn, but still). After6...Ne7the same sequence7.h4?!h58.Nf4doesn't make sense because Black can simply take8...hxg4and doesn't have to worry about9.Nxg6Nxg6, as White just wrecks his own pawn structure on the kingside for very little in return.Basically, White has to decide on a different plan of action than after6...c5, because the main moves after6...c5(which are7.h4and7.Be3)make no sense at all after 6... Ne7. Meanwhile we still want to play ...c5, but a better prepared version.} 
7. Be3 {As mentioned, 7. h4 is similarly bad. Still, you'll face both those moves from time to time, because a lot of white players don't understand that 6... c5 and 6... Ne7 require a wholly different approach from White.} 
7. h5 {Of course, we can and should attack the weakness on g4.} 
8. Nf4
8. hxg4
9. Nxg6
9. Nxg6
10. Qxg4
10. c5 {White's center is weak and his pawn structure is also not great.} 
11. dxc5 {If11.Bd3,11...Qh4!is a nice response.} 
11. Nxe5 {Black has natural play with ...Nbc6 and ...Qh4 being the next moves. White has no compensation for his shattered pawn structure.} 
