4. Nc3 {As mentioned, this used to be the mainline some 20 years ago. I have fond memories of this variation, spending many hours studying the ideas, as one of the members of the local chess club would always play it against me.The idea of 4. Nc3, apart from that it develops the knight, is quite crude - White waits for Black to play ...e6 (which he inevitably has to play sooner or later) and the knight takes away the e4-square, so that White can start chasing the bishop with g4 and h4 next.} 
4. e6 {Black should oblige as the resulting positions are fine for him, even if it can become crazy complicated.} 
5. g4
5. Bg6
6. Nge2 {This move is White's idea - the knight is coming to f4 to further harass the bishop on g6. The immediate6.h4?doesn't make sense as Black can oppose this pawn with6...h5!,when g4 sticks out as a sore thumb.After6.Nge2Black has an interesting choice to make. The mainline was and still is6...c5, and you can find this in Erwin L'Ami's LTR. Black is completely fine in that line, though play remains incredibly sharp and tactical.} 
6. Ne7 {This was my pet line against 4. Nc3. It's a fully valid alternative to 6... c5, with less theory and (arguably) less sharp resulting positions, though the positions are still very tactical.I've also dabbled in6...f6from time to time, but the verdict nowadays seems to be that Black doesn't fully equalize there, e.g. in the variation7.h4!fxe58.h5!Bf79.dxe5.The idea behind6...Ne7is that Black first reinforces the bishop on g6 before deciding on further action. One problem with6...c5is that after7.h4h58.Nf4Black faces an issue with the h5-pawn (to be fair, nowadays we understand that Black can perfectly well sacrifice that pawn, but still). After6...Ne7the same sequence7.h4?!h58.Nf4doesn't make sense because Black can simply take8...hxg4and doesn't have to worry about9.Nxg6Nxg6, as White just wrecks his own pawn structure on the kingside for very little in return.Basically, White has to decide on a different plan of action than after6...c5, because the main moves after6...c5(which are7.h4and7.Be3)make no sense at all after 6... Ne7. Meanwhile we still want to play ...c5, but a better prepared version.} 
7. f4 {This is an interesting try, provided White knows how to follow it up.7.Ng3is also occasionally seen, but most of the time transposes to 7. f4 after7...c58.f4h5.One of the ideas of f4 is that White usually wants to entomb the g6-bishop. This happens for instance after7.f4h58.f5!exf59.g5with the idea to follow up with--10.Nf4.} 
7. c5
8. dxc5 {This was played a few times by Shirov, one of the main proponents of the 4. Nc3 variation, in a rapid match against Vallejo.} 
8. h5 {Vallejo played8...Nec6, which is not bad, but leads to a type of play I don't like after9.h4h510.f5exf511.Nf4. However, in this line I do want to mention the possibility9...Be7!?which Stockfish likes very much. One of the ideas is10.h5Bh4+11.Kd2Be4when White can't exchange on e4 because it would lead to the loss of his queen.} 
 {I want to propose a very typical piece sacrifice that's implied by 8... h5!?} 9. f5
9. hxg4 {That's the idea. Such a piece sac often works well when we still have a knight on e7, as we can recapture after10.fxg6with10...Nxg6.} 
10. fxg6
10. Nxg6 {Now White has to be very accurate in order not to get a seriously worse position. Nxe5-f3+ is a very annoying idea, while Black has very easy play with ...Nbc6 and ...Bxc5 being natural moves.White would love to play11.Nd4in such a position, but it runs into11...Qh4+.} 
11. Qd4 {The only move that keeps the balance. White temporarily prevents ...Nxe5 and relocates the queen to the kingside, getting rid of the g4-pawn.} 
11. Nc6
12. Qxg4
12. Bxc5 {Now taking on e5 followed by an invasion on h4 is a key idea for Black.} 
13. Qg3
13. Be7 {The threat of ...Bh4 forces White to play14.Kd1. The line could continue14...Bh415.Qg1Ngxe5and next is16.--Qf6.Black only has two pawns for the piece, but White's lack of coordination means the compensation is more than enough.} 
