[White "7) Advance with 3...Bf5: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly"]
[Black "4. Nc3 Shirov Attack with 6... Ne7!? #7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. Nc3 {As mentioned, this used to be the mainline some 20 years ago. I have fond memories of this variation, spending many hours studying the ideas, as one of the members of the local chess club would always play it against me.The idea of 4. Nc3, apart from that it develops the knight, is quite crude - White waits for Black to play ...e6 (which he inevitably has to play sooner or later) and the knight takes away the e4-square, so that White can start chasing the bishop with g4 and h4 next.} 
4. e6 {Black should oblige as the resulting positions are fine for him, even if it can become crazy complicated.} 
5. g4
5. Bg6
6. Nge2 {This move is White's idea - the knight is coming to f4 to further harass the bishop on g6. The immediate6.h4?doesn't make sense as Black can oppose this pawn with6...h5!,when g4 sticks out as a sore thumb.After6.Nge2Black has an interesting choice to make. The mainline was and still is6...c5, and you can find this in Erwin L'Ami's LTR. Black is completely fine in that line, though play remains incredibly sharp and tactical.} 
6. Ne7 {This was my pet line against 4. Nc3. It's a fully valid alternative to 6... c5, with less theory and (arguably) less sharp resulting positions, though the positions are still very tactical.I've also dabbled in6...f6from time to time, but the verdict nowadays seems to be that Black doesn't fully equalize there, e.g. in the variation7.h4!fxe58.h5!Bf79.dxe5.The idea behind6...Ne7is that Black first reinforces the bishop on g6 before deciding on further action. One problem with6...c5is that after7.h4h58.Nf4Black faces an issue with the h5-pawn (to be fair, nowadays we understand that Black can perfectly well sacrifice that pawn, but still). After6...Ne7the same sequence7.h4?!h58.Nf4doesn't make sense because Black can simply take8...hxg4and doesn't have to worry about9.Nxg6Nxg6, as White just wrecks his own pawn structure on the kingside for very little in return.Basically, White has to decide on a different plan of action than after6...c5, because the main moves after6...c5(which are7.h4and7.Be3)make no sense at all after 6... Ne7. Meanwhile we still want to play ...c5, but a better prepared version.} 
7. Nf4 {This is the mainline. White first has to put the knight on f4 before he can play h4-h5.} 
7. c5 {There's not much else to do. It makes sense to undermine White's center at this moment, especially as the knight on f4 can't recapture on d4 anymore.At this point White has two main moves.8.h4is the most played, but around the turn of the millennium attention switched to8.dxc5when it was shown that8.h4leads to a draw by force.} 
8. h4 {Now the following moves are more or less forced.} 
8. cxd4
9. Nb5 {9.Qxd4?Nbc610.Qd1h5!is just terrible for White.} 
9. Nec6 {We shouldn't allow the knight to d6 uncontested.} 
10. h5 {White has gained some time to challenge the g6-bishop.} 
10. Be4 {The bishop will remain trapped after White plays11.f3, but we force White to make some concessions before giving up the piece.} 
11. f3
11. a6 {The inferior11...Bxf3?was played a number of times until it was shown that11...a6is the way to go. Now White has a choice between trying to win a piece with12.Nd6+or agreeing to exchange some pieces with12.fxe4axb513.exd5exd5.That position is not exactly challenging for Black though, as we can smoothly develop with ...Bb4+ and ... Nd7 and the e5-pawn is weak.} 
12. Nd6+
12. Bxd6
13. exd6
13. g5 {Vishy Anand came up with this idea, effectively killing the line starting with 8. h4. Here,14.hxg6?Bxg6isn't possible as it would free the e4-bishop. Therefore White has to retreat the knight to an unfortunate spot, and Black gets the chance to create a massive pawn phalanx.} 
14. Nh3
14. h6
15. fxe4
15. dxe4
16. Bg2
16. f5 {Soon the d6-pawn will fall and Black will have 3 pawns for the piece and a gigantic center. It's actually surprising that White is not just clearly worse or even losing here. Since he's ahead in development there are some tactical shots available that should lead to a draw.} 
17. O-O {17.gxf5exf518.O-OO-Oleads to the same thing.} 
17. O-O
18. gxf5
18. exf5 {The rest is not super important to know, as it's White who has to figure out what to do. Basically, only the sequence19.Bxe4!fxe420.Bxg5!saves White, when all the games in the database end in a draw after20...Rxf1+21.Qxf1hxg522.Qf5Qd723.Qg6+followed by a perpetual check. Actually, the computer thinks Black would do well to decline the second piece with21...Qxd622.Qf5Nd7for some reason, but that's food for correspondence players.If White plays anything other than 19.Bxe4 Black will just take the pawn on d6 and enjoy a crushing position.} 
