8. dxc5 {Unlike after8.h4,now White no longer has to worry about the d4-pawn while hunting the bishop on g6.} 
8. Nec6 {In my old copy of the Advance Variation by Karpov & Podgaets from 2006 this move was criticized, and the authors claimed that it was better to go for the e-pawn with the other knight. Actually, with my proposed line it doesn't matter which knight is used, as play is likely to transpose anyway. Still, it feels more natural to me to use the e7-knight, which was blocking the bishop on f8.The other way to the same position would be8...Nd79.h4Nxe510.Bg2and now10...N7c6!?transposes.} 
9. h4 {This was the point of 8. dxc5. There aren't really any alternatives worth considering for White.} 
9. Nxe5
10. Bg2 {10.h5leads to an endgame after10...Be411.Nxe4dxe412.Qxd8+Kxd813.Bg2Nbd714.Bxe4Nxc5.Here White would be doing well with the bishop pair if the e4-bishop and g4-pawn weren't both hanging.After10.Bg2we reach the critical position for this variation, as White is now (seemingly) prepared to continue with--11.h5Be412.f3. The dozen or so games that reached this position all continued either10...h5or10...h6. But Stockfish indicates that it isn't necessary to safeguard the bishop!} 
10. Nbc6 {My proposed novelty, just developing and intending once again to sacrifice the bishop if necessary.} 
11. h5
11. Be4
12. f3 {I don't see what else White should do. For instance, after12.Nxe4dxe413.Qxd8+Rxd814.Bxe4Bxc5Black's coordination & activity balances out the bishop pair - the g4-pawn is hanging and Black could try something like15.--Rd416.Bg2?!Nb4!.} 
12. g5 {Once again this pawn thrust comes to the rescue.} 
13. Nh3 {One very important detail to note is that13.fxe4should be answered by the in-between move13...d4!,shutting down the g2-bishop and making the knight on e5 a monster before recapturing a knight.} 
13. Bxf3 {This seems the best way to give up the bishop.13...h614.fxe4d415.Nb1Bxc5would see us blocking our own dark-squared bishop.} 
14. Bxf3
14. h6 {Our next move is ...Bxc5. White can't protect the c5-pawn as15.Be3?runs into15...d4.In this variation we only get two pawns for the piece, but our coordination is much better than White's and most of his pieces are biting on granite. The position is approximately equal. A few lines to support this assessment:A)15.O-OBxc5+16.Kh1f5!17.Qe217.gxf5?!g4!regains the piece as18.Bxg4?Qh419.Rf4Rg8-+followed by taking on g4 gives Black a winning attack17...O-O18.Bd2Qd719.Rae1and Black has a nice choice between advancing either19...d4or19...f4, in both cases with a nice position.B)15.Nf2!?(this seems the more purposeful to me, intending to exchange the e5-knight as soon as possible)15...Bxc516.Nd3Nxd3+17.Qxd3O-Oand White has difficulty developing as short castling is illegal,18.Be3?runs into18...Bxe319.Qxe3d4-+,18.Bd2?Nb4!at least wins the c2-pawn with check, and18.b3?Ne5!19.Qe2Bd4leads to tactical problems as well, e.g.20.Bd2Qc7-+.} 
