4. h5
5. Bd3 {A trendy line that is perhaps White's most annoying variation in the entire Caro-Kann Advance complex nowadays. White just wants to exchange bishops, claiming that (after the inevitable ...e6) the insertion of h2-h4 and h7-h5 is to White's benefit, as the g5-square can be used to stage a kingside attack but also to annoy Black in general.} 
5. Qd7 {I'll admit that this is a subpar answer to 5. Bd3. However, it does have some practical benefits: Firstly, it will immediately get your opponent out of book, as this move has practically never been tried. For example, it is not mentioned in any of the courses on Chessable that advocate this line for White. Secondly, it's also not immediately obvious how to punish Black for making this strange queen move. Clearly6.Bxf5Qxf5would just help Black.I'm not sure how to feel about 5...Qd7 in general. I haven't been able to find a clear refutation, although no doubt White should get some slight advantage at least in some lines. At the same time it seems the computer is overstating White's advantage to some degree. I probably wouldn't play 5...Qd7 in a classical game, but it seems great material for blitz and rapid.} 
6. Be3 {This is the computer's favorite move, and while it looks a bit obscure, there is a good deal of logic to it. Aside from just developing a piece, White is not committing the g1-knight yet, leaving Black to guess as to White's setup. White is also anticipating c6-c5 by putting the bishop on e3.Finally, there is a neat tactical detail that6...Nh6?!doesn't really work right now due to7.Qxh5!. (Meanwhile, after6.Bg5,6...Nh6!does work because of7.Qxh5??Bg4trapping the queen - another nice detail to be aware of).} 
6. g6 {As we can't play6...Nh6for reasons explained above, we first need to guard the h5-pawn in order to prepare this move.} 
7. Nc3
7. Nh6
8. Nce2 {This seems an interesting plan - the queenside knight is brought to g3.} 
8. Ng4
9. Bg5 {White should not allow ...Nxe3.} 
9. c5 {This is the downside of moving the bishop from e3 (and of allowing Black's knight to g4).} 
10. Nf3 {If10.f3Nh611.dxc5Bg712.Bf4a6!followed by Nc6 Black will soon regain the pawn with at least equality.} 
10. Nc6 {Black is doing well and can consider harassing the g5-bishop further with ...f6 next.} 
