[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Advance with 3...Bf5: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly"]
[Black "4.Nf3 Mainline: why not 13...Kc8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. Nf3
4. e6
5. Be2
5. c5
6. Be3
6. Qb6
7. Nc3
7. Nc6
8. O-O {There are some alternatives for White at this point in8.Na4,8.dxc5and8.Bb5which I won't cover here. I'll refer you to Erwin's LTR for the deetz.} 
8. Qxb2 {The right moment to capture on b2. If we compare this to the previous move, here9.Qb1?would not be good for White because after9...Qxb110.Raxb1Black is ready to play10...O-O-O!with a solid extra pawn. If we had captured 7... Qxb2? with the knight back on b8, the same line is terrible for Black because White's rook will enter on b7.} 
9. Qe1 {Here9.Nb5is an alternative (again, see LTR Caro-Kann for specifics) when9...c4!leads to a very good version for Black of the lines that we're about to examine.} 
9. c4 {Instead the main line continues9...cxd410.Bxd4Nxd411.Nxd4Bb412.Rb1Bxc313.Rxb2Bxe114.Rxe1b6. White has good compensation for the pawn but Black should be able to defend this endgame.L'Ami commented on9...c4that he spent a lot of time trying to make it work for Black, but it doesn't seem to equalize. I agree, but the positions reached are very hard to play for White (even the computer struggles to find the right path to an advantage) and, unless your opponent knows you are going to play9...c4and has specifically prepared for it, I think it's very unlikely they will know how to navigate the resulting positions. In other words: it's a good way to mix things up if you don't fancy defending a very slightly worse endgame after9...cxd4instead.} 
10. Rb1 {White's only try, as the queen has to be evicted from b2. After most other moves Black will take on c2 next and White's compensation for the pawns is truly dubious.} 
10. Qa3 {Now White will gain an important tempo with11.Nb5and win the rook with a check on c7. However, the knight will be trapped in the corner and Black already has one pawn for the exchange and is eyeing two others (a2 and c2).} 
11. Nb5
11. Qa4 {11...Qxa2unfortunately doesn't work for concrete reasons:12.Nc7+Kd813.Nxa8Kc814.Ra1Qxc215.Rxa7!Nxa716.Qa5and White gets a winning attack.15.Nb6+should also win, by the way. This line shows that Black first needs to stabilize a bit before grabbing additional pawns. (Also, the c2-pawn is often more important than the a2-pawn.)} 
12. Nc7+
12. Kd7 {12...Kd8amounts to the same thing if Black wants to play 13... Kc8 next, but if Black wants to play 13...b5 the king is better on d7.} 
13. Nxa8 {Now Black has to make a fundamental choice between13...b5and13...Kc8. Both have their pros and cons. Stockfish likes13...Kc8a bit better, though it thinks White (with best play) has at the very least a clear advantage after either move.Essentially,13...Kc8is more conservative, as Black aims to finish development and capture the knight with Kb8xa8.13...b5is more energetic, protecting the b7-pawn by advancing it, and intending to catch White's knight eventually by playing ...Ba3 or ...Bb4, ...Nge7 or ...Nh6 and ...Rxa8.} 
13. Kc8
14. Ng5 {The direct counter-attack against f7 seems to be White's best move, leading to some advantage. Let me show you some of White's possible alternatives to give you a feel for the type of positions and ideas that arise:A:14.Nb6+?Some white players might be tempted to give this check and 'win' a pawn for the knight on b6, but this is not the right moment. As a general rule it is pretty much never good for White to play this move unless Black has already spent a tempo on ...Kb8 and is intending to play ...Kxa8 next.14...axb615.Rxb6Kc7!16.Rb1Qxc217.Rc1Qa418.Nh4Bb419.Qd1Qxd120.Rfxd1Nge7-+I wanted to show this position. Black has only one pawn for the exchange, but is probably winning. So the early Nb6+ is not a good idea and allows Black to push White around.B:14.Nh4Not the right knight move, but it's an instructive line as it shows how Black can easily get the upper hand if play goes into an endgame.14...Bxc215.Bd1!Otherwise Black can continue with ... Bb4 and ...Ne7 with a large advantage. At least now White gets to exchange one of his useless bishops for Black's useful one.15...Bxd116.Qxd1Qxd117.Rfxd1Be7!An important move to insert.18.Nf3Kb819.Nb6axb620.Rxb6Bd8!This is why 17...Be7! was important.21.Rbb1h622.Kf1Nge723.g4Ba5⩱Black can slowly prepare an advance of the b-pawn and is the one pushing in this endgame.C:14.c3?!Anand played a similar idea in the 13... b5 line, so some players (if they're aware of that game) might try it here as well. White wants to free their game by giving back the exchange on b1. Black shouldn't take it immediately.14...Ba3!15.Ng5Nd816.Qd2Bxb117.Rxb1Ne7And again Black is pushing for an advantage.D:14.Qd2This is a slightly worse version of 14. Qc3.14...Bb415.c3Bxb116.Rxb1Ba3The position will normalize once Nb6+ axb6 happens.17.Ng5Nd818.Nb6+axb619.Rxb6h620.Nf3Ne7Objectively the position is equal, but there is room to play for a win for both sides.E:14.Qc3!?Not a bad move at all, but a bit computerish.14...Bb4!?15.Qb2Qxc216.Nh4!Only this way White can pose some problems to Black. Now White is threatening 17. Nxf5 Qxf5 18. Bd2.16...Qxb217.Rxb2Nge718.Nxf5Nxf519.Bg4!The only move that doesn't concede a large disadvantage! It's based on some very specific tactics that we'll now see.19...Ba320.Rb5!Again the only move.20...Nfxd421.Rxd5That's the point.21...h5!?The complications continue on for a very long time from here. I think the line from 16.Nh4! up until here is incredibly unlikely to happen (unless we're talking correspondence chess) as it's very engine-like play, and any minor deviation sees White immediately being worse or outright losing.F:14.Bd1!?This is White's second best option according to the engine. It prepares 15. Nh4, as the immediate 14. Nh4 would let Black gain a tempo on the rook on b1 with ...Bxc2.14...Qxa2There's no good alternative.15.Be2!And White goes back to e2! Now with the open a-file there are ideas of Ra1 followed by Rxa7 or even Nb6+ and Ra8+ has become a thing. White has to have a very vivid imagination to consider the maneuver Be2-d1-e2 - or engine preparation has shown them this idea.15...Qxc216.Rc1This seems to be White's best continuation. White prepares to sacrifice a piece on c4 for a central breakthrough with d4-d5.16...Qb2This is the engine's main continuation, but after White's following sacrifice it becomes very messy.17.Bxc4!dxc418.d5Bb4!19.Qd1exd5At this point White has a choice between several interesting moves - 20. Qxd5, 20. Bxa7 and 20. Nd4. I'll just show the latter.20.Nd4This looks a bit slow but it seems to be White's best move.20...Nge7Black can't allow White to ruin his pawn structure with Nxc6.21.Nxf5Nxf522.Bxa7!Nxa723.Nb6+Kb824.Qxd5Nc6It's best to immediately bring this knight back into the game.25.Qxf7Nfe726.Nxc4Qe2The queen is relatively safe and active here, while keeping an eye on e5, f2 and c4. White is probably still a bit better in this position, but it's playable for Black and anything could happen in a game.I should say that there are tons of tactical details and possible alternatives that I omitted to keep the comments brief. The positions after 13...Kc8 are very rich!} 
 {Now let's consider White's best move, 14. Ng5!} 14. Nh6 {14...Bg6looks natural, but15.Bg4!surprisingly leads to a winning advantage for White. The idea is twofold: If15...Nh6there is16.Bxe6+!fxe617.Nxe6and the a8-knight is rescued via c7, while if15...Kb8, then16.Nc7!?Kxc717.f4!gives White a winning attack with the sequence--18.f5exf519.Bf3.} 
15. Bh5 {White should first provoke another retreat or weakening before putting the bishop on d1. Ultimately this position is why I couldn't in good conscience make 13... Kc8 trainable, as I didn't find a good answer for Black here.} 
15. Nd8 {I analyzed15...g6for a long time as it seem to me the most natural way of defending the f7-pawn, but unfortunately it doesn't work because the bishop on f5 gets trapped after the following sequence:16.Bd1!Qxa217.Rb5Qa417.Rb2Qa119.Nb6+!axb620.Rxb6Kc721.Rxc6+!Kxc622.h3!with the idea to continue g2-g4, which Black can't really do anything about. The computer line continues a lot farther:22...Qb223.g4Bb424.Qe2Be725.gxf5Bxg526.Bxg5Nxf5.Black already has two pawns for the piece and will get a third one, but still after the exact continuation27.c3!Qxc328.Qa2!Qxd429.Bc2Rb830.Rb1Qc531.Ba4+Kc732.Bb5,even with four pawns for the piece, Black faces a strong attack and will probably lose material sooner or later.Another possibility is15...Bb416.c3Be7, but after17.Bxf7!Bxg518.Bxe6+Bxe619.Bxg5Nf7,even if Black eventually captures the knight on a8 and queens are exchanged, it seems to be difficult to defend Black's position as White has the easy plan of pushing the kingside pawns forward.15...Nd8is a bit passive and White should be able to get some advantage, but it's not immediately lost.} 
16. Bd1 {Just like after 15... g6, here the retreat16.Bd1is critical as well. Here Black can't capture either c2 or a2:16...Bxc2?17.Bxc2Qxc218.Qa5!leads to a winning attack (here we see a downside of having played the c6-knight to d8), while after16...Qxa2?White can sacrifice the bishop with17.Bg4!to continue17...Bxg418.Ra1Qxc219.Qa5.} 
16. Kb8 {Black doesn't have a good square to develop the f8-bishop to, so he first clarifies the situation with the a8-knight.} 
17. Nb6 {The position changes drastically with each move! Here17.c3?is terrible for White because after17...Qxa2the rook has no good square to go to (e.g.18.Rc1Ba3) while Black no longer has to be afraid of White bringing the heavy pieces to the a-file.} 
17. axb6
18. Rxb6
18. Kc7
19. Rb2
19. Ba3
20. Rb1
20. Be7
21. Qc3
21. b5
22. a3
22. Nc6
23. h3 {Once again the idea of trapping Black's light-squared bishop is a big theme. I'm not 100% sure whether Black gets enough compensation. Play could continue as follows:} 
23. Ra8
24. g4
24. Bg6
25. h4
25. Qxa3
26. Qxa3
26. Rxa3
27. h5
27. Bxc2
28. Bxc2
28. Nxg4
29. Nxf7
29. Nxe3
30. fxe3
30. Rxe3
31. Rxb5
31. Nxd4 {And the pawns might compensate for the rook; at the very least Black is not clearly losing.} 
