13. b5 {I decided to make this move trainable, as I think it creates more opportunities for White to go wrong. With best play White can get a large advantage, but if you want to play something that is fully correct, you should play 9...cxd4 instead of 9...c4.I should mention that 13...b5 was featured in two high-level games in this variation, although they were not classical games. Anand-Xiong was an online rapid game and Grischuk-Shimanov an online blitz game. White won both games, but Black soon got a very good position in both of them... Let's see them.} 
14. Bd1 {The best move and played by Grischuk. Black has to use some time to develop his kingside, and White uses this opportunity to defend the c2-pawn, intending to chase the f5-bishop with Nh4 next. There is also the idea of playing Qd2 followed by c3 and Bc2, if Black allows this.} 
14. Bb4 {14...h615.Nh4Bh716.f4!leads to a winning initiative for White. Meanwhile,14...Be7is a bit too cooperative, as White can then play15.Qd2intending 16. c3 and 17. Bc2, when White is coordinating quite well and Black's compensation for the exchange seems insufficient.} 
15. Bd2
15. Be7 {15...Bxd216.Qxd2Nge717.c3!Qa518.Bc2is a good demonstration of what White wants to achieve with 14. Bd1.} 
16. a3 {A calm attempt to block up the queenside before starting play on the kingside, which is a good try for a small edge for White.} 
16. Nh6 {Black can't take the a-pawn -16...Qxa3?17.Rxb5is obvious, while16...Bxa3?17.Ra1is a pin that can't be solved.} 
17. c3
17. Qa6
18. Ra1 {18.Rb2is also good, albeit less intuitive.} 
18. Rxa8
19. Be2 {This move is more or less necessary, which becomes apparent from a variation like19.Bxh6gxh620.Qe3(this is what White would like to play) when Black not only has20...Bd3, but also20...b4!thanks to the unprotected rook on a1.} 
19. Qb6 {Black needs to play for the ...b4 break, and the preparatory move ...a5 is necessary for that. At this point Stockfish still thinks White has a small advantage, but a line like20.Bxh6gxh621.Qd2a5!22.Qxh6Ra7!followed by ...b4 sees Black with a fair share of the chances, despite being an exchange down.} 
