2. d5
3. e5
3. Bf5
4. Nf3
4. e6
5. Be2
5. c5
6. Be3
6. Qb6
7. Nc3
7. Nc6
8. O-O {There are some alternatives for White at this point in8.Na4,8.dxc5and8.Bb5which I won't cover here. I'll refer you to Erwin's LTR for the deetz.} 
8. Qxb2 {The right moment to capture onb2. If we compare this to the previous move, here9.Qb1?would not be good for White because after9...Qxb110.Raxb1Black is ready to play10...O-O-O!with a solid extra pawn. If we had captured 7... Qxb2? with the knight back on b8, the same line is terrible for Black because White's rook will enter on b7.} 
9. Qe1 {Here9.Nb5is an alternative (again, see LTR Caro-Kann for specifics) when9...c4!leads to a very good version for Black of the lines that we're about to examine.} 
9. c4 {Instead the main line continues9...cxd410.Bxd4Nxd411.Nxd4Bb412.Rb1Bxc313.Rxb2Bxe114.Rxe1b6. White has good compensation for the pawn but Black should be able to defend this endgame.L'Ami commented on9...c4that he spent a lot of time trying to make it work for Black, but it doesn't seem to equalize. I agree, but the positions reached are very hard to play for White (even the computer struggles to find the right path to an advantage) and, unless your opponent knows you are going to play9...c4and has specifically prepared for it, I think it's very unlikely they will know how to navigate the resulting positions. In other words: it's a good way to mix things up if you don't fancy defending a very slightly endgame after9...cxd4instead.} 
10. Rb1 {White's only try, as the queen has to be evicted from b2. After most other moves Black will take on c2 next and White's compensation for the pawns is truly dubious.} 
10. Qa3 {Now White will gain an important tempo with11.Nb5and win the rook with a check on c7. However, the knight will be trapped in the corner and Black already has one pawn for the exchange and is eyeing two others (a2 and c2).} 
11. Nb5
11. Qa4 {11...Qxa2unfortunately doesn't work for concrete reasons:12.Nc7+Kd813.Nxa8Kc814.Ra1Qxc215.Rxa7!Nxa716.Qa5and White gets a winning attack.15.Nb6+should also win, by the way. This line shows that Black first needs to stabilize a bit before grabbing additional pawns. (Also, the c2-pawn is often more important than the a2-pawn.)} 
12. Nc7+
12. Kd7 {12...Kd8amounts to the same thing if Black wants to play 13... Kc8 next, but if Black wants to play 13...b5 the king is better on d7.} 
13. Nxa8 {Now Black has to make a fundamental choice between13...b5and13...Kc8. Both have their pros and cons. Stockfish likes13...Kc8a bit better, though it thinks White (with best play) has at the very least a clear advantage after either move.Essentially,13...Kc8is more conservative, as Black aims to finish development and capture the knight with Kb8xa8.13...b5is more energetic, protecting the b7-pawn by advancing it, and intending to catch White's knight eventually by playing ...Ba3 or ...Bb4, ...Nge7 or ...Nh6 and ...Rxa8.} 
13. b5 {I decided to make this move trainable, as I think it creates more opportunities for White to go wrong. With best play White can get a large advantage, but if you want to play something that is fully correct, you should play 9...cxd4 instead of 9...c4.I should mention that 13...b5 was featured in two high-level games in this variation, although they were not classical games. Anand-Xiong was an online rapid game and Grischuk-Shimanov an online blitz game. White won both games, but Black soon got a very good position in both of them... Let's see them.} 
14. Bd1 {The best move and played by Grischuk. Black has to use some time to develop his kingside, and White uses this opportunity to defend the c2-pawn, intending to chase the f5-bishop with Nh4 next. There is also the idea of playing Qd2 followed by c3 and Bc2, if Black allows this.} 
14. Bb4 {14...h615.Nh4Bh716.f4!leads to a winning initiative for White. Meanwhile,14...Be7is a bit too cooperative, as White can then play15.Qd2intending 16. c3 and 17. Bc2, when White is coordinating quite well and Black's compensation for the exchange seems insufficient.} 
15. Bd2
15. Be7 {15...Bxd216.Qxd2Nge717.c3!Qa518.Bc2is a good demonstration of what White wants to achieve with 14. Bd1.} 
16. g4 {This unlikely pawn thrust is a major headache for Black.} 
16. Bg6 {This would be my suggestion.The tactical problem with16...Bxg4is the line17.c3!Qa618.a4!bxa419.Ng5!and Black can't defend against all the different threats, apparently. I'll admit to not really understanding everything that's going on in that position, though.16...Be4is also interesting, and I spent an hour analyzing it, but I was unable to solve the following:17.Ng5(again!)17...Bxg518.Bxg5h619.f3!Bh720.Bh4g521.Bg3Nge722.f4and here Black has 6(!) interesting alternatives -22...gxf4,22...b4,22...Bxc2,22...Be422...Rxa8and even22...Rb8- but ultimately, with best play it seems White gets a close to winning position in each case.} 
17. Ng5 {After playing 16.g4 White needs to continue their kingside assault with f2-f4-f5, and the knight needs to move for that.17.h4?h5!is not the way to go about it.} 
17. Nh6 {We should at least keep developing. After17...h6Stockfish gives the fantastic18.Nxf7!!Bxf719.c3Qa620.a4!bxa421.Bxa4!!Qxa422.Rb7+Ke823.f4!followed by--24.f5and a winning attack for White. Just look at the miserable knight on g8.} 
18. f4
18. Bxc2 {We'd rather not make this capture as it drops the b5-pawn in turn, but there isn't much choice here as f4-f5 was coming.For instance,18...Rxa8?19.f5!exf520.e6+Kc721.gxf5Nxf522.c3Qa623.exf7and with Ne6+ coming next White is winning.} 
19. f5 {This is too rushed.} 
19. Rxa8
20. fxe6+ {Or20.Bxc2Qxc221.Rxb5Bxg521...c3is also a fascinating option22.Bxg5Nxd423.fxe6+fxe624.Rf2Qd3and despite the tension, the game might end in a draw soon, e.g.25.Qb4Qd1+26.Kg2Qxg4+etc.} 
20. fxe6
21. Bxc2
21. Qxc2
22. Rxb5
22. Rf8 {This would be my suggestion in order to keep the game going.22...c3is playable if you want more crazy stuff, although the position becomes extremely wild after23.Rb7+. Meanwhile,22...Bxg523.Bxg5Nxd4transposes to the variation 20.Bxc2 which could lead to a perpetual check.22...Rf8seems more controlled. White might now be tempted by23.Rb7+?!Kc824.Rc7+?Kxc725.Nxe6+Kc826.Nxf8Nxd4when, once again, White has a trapped knight behind enemy lines. Moreover, Black simply has a winning attack here, with ideas like ...Nxg4, ...Bc5, ...Qd3-Ne2+.Instead, White should play23.Rxf8+Bxf8,but then faces a difficult position. Stockfish gives 0.00, but Black has a pawn for an exchange, a safer king, and three of White's pawns are hanging. There still are a lot of interesting ideas in the position, so I would encourage you to explore it further.} 
