21. h3 {This seems to be the only way to secure a substantial advantage for White. The h6-knight is locked out of play for the moment, while White can sacrifice the d4-pawn to generate an attack on the queenside.21.Bc3?!Nxg4is difficult to handle for White, while21.f5Bxg5would transpose to19.f5Rxa820.Bxc2Qxc221.Rxb5Bxg5.} 
21. Bd8 {I first wanted to recommend21...Nxd4- after all, what is more natural than taking a central pawn with an attack on a rook, activating the knight? However, concretely the following is problematic for Black:22.Rb7+Ke823.Bb4!Bd8!24.Qe3Bb625.Kh1!and in pretty much every variation it's White who has all the fun.21...Bd8looks a bit passive, but it has a good deal of logic to it. Firstly, in some variations there is the resource Rb7+ followed by Rxe7, which is now dealt with. Secondly, we're still eyeing the idea of ...Bb6 with pressure on d4. But at the same time, the bishop keeps an eye on the g5-knight, which prevents White from playing f4-f5 in some variations.} 
22. Bc3 {Some other lines:  A: The immediate22.Rb7?!Kc8doesn't do anything for White.B:22.f5?!Nxd423.Rb7+and now23...Kc6!is a resource that wouldn't have been available with the bishop still on e7.C:22.Be3Qd323.Kg2!Rc824.f5exf525.Rxd5+Ke826.gxf5Ne7!is a crazy tactical mess.22.Bc3has the advantage that22...Qd3is now met by23.Rf3.The downside is that the bishop no longer protects the g5-knight in case of f4-f5.} 
22. Qxa2 {I'll end the line with this pawn grab. Black now has two pawns for the exchange, and a defensible position, though White is firmly in control and can obviously push for a win. But, after White plays Nf3 and f5, I still don't see an easy knock-out punch for White. There is one funny line that I do want to show you:23.Nxh7Bb624.Qe3?!Rh825.Ng5?Qh2+!!and Black wins after26.Kxh2Nxg4+27.Kg2Nxe3followed by28.--Nf5.This seems to be the best White can do in the line 9...c4 with 13...b5. White has to find some unlikely moves (especially 16.g4!), and I don't think anyone would get close to the final position after 22.Bc3 Qxa2 in an over the board game. As we've seen, even luminaries like Anand and Grischuk have gone wrong very early on in this variation. So unless you're playing on grandmaster level, feel free to play into this variation and the fascinating chaos it produces.} 
