[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Classical Variation: 4...Bf5 With 7...e6"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {3.Nd2dxe4amounts to the same thing. This is the so-called 'Classical' Caro-Kann, which was very popular from the mid-20th century up until the early 2010s, but it has fallen out of fashion nowadays. Still, there is nothing wrong at all with White's setup.} 
3. dxe4
4. Nxe4
4. Bf5 {Here the mainline of4...Nf65.Nxf6exf6seems to have defanged the 3.Nc3/3.Nd2 variation. It continues6.c3Bd67.Bd3O-O8.Qc2Re8+9.Ne2and now9...h5!equalizes for Black. This 4...Nf6 line is analyzed in some detail in both LTR: Caro-Kann and Keep It Simple for Black.The more traditional mainline of4...Bf5holds up well too, but it's a lot more lines to memorize and in some variations White gets a hair-raising attack and Black has to find some complicated defensive maneuvers, after which the game usually ends in some perpetual or repetition of moves. I want to suggest a sideline of 4...Bf5, however, which significantly cuts down on the theory.} 
5. Ng3
5. Bg6
6. h4 {White also has some other tries, usually involving a setup with6.Bc4and/or developing the g1-knight to f4 via e2 or h3, which I am not going to analyze here.} 
6. h6
7. Nf3 {Here the traditional mainline continues with7...Nd7,as White is 'threatening' to move the f3-knight to the e5-square, gaining a tempo on the bishop on g6 in the process (as, after playing ...h6, Black definitely doesn't want to allow Nxg6 fxg6 wrecking his pawn structure).However, there are two interesting sidelines here in7...Nf6and7...e6with which Black allows White to carry out this 'threat'.} 
7. e6 {Allowing White to play Ne5. The counterargument to the main move 7...Nd7 is that the b8-knight is not ideal on d7 - it would be better if Black could play ...c5 and then ...Nc6. By first playing ...e6 and delaying the development of the b8-knight, we keep open that possibility.Secondly, if White moves the knight to e5 early on, it can become a target there. Finally, of course,7...e6contains a lot less theory than the mainline7...Nd78.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3etc. Not to mention that your opponent will be less likely to know what to do against it.} 
8. Ne5 {The most-played move and White's principled attempt to punish Black for 'forgetting' to play ...Nd7.There are two alternatives in8.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3Nf6and the similar8.Bd3Bxd39.Qxd3Nf6.I don't find these lines very troublesome, because in the worst case Black could transpose to the traditional mainlines by playing ...Nd7 on the next move, but I've tried to travel less theory-heavy roads with an immediate ...c5 followed by ...Nc6 instead.} 
8. Bh7
9. Bd3 {After pushing our light-squared bishop around, White exchanges it, just as in the old mainline of 4... Bf5.  There are a few minor alternatives here in 9. Bc4 and 9. Qh5.} 
9. Bxd3 {Taking the d4-pawn is not just dubious, but loses immediately to a tactic worth knowing:9...Qxd4?10.Nxf7!Kxf711.Bg6+and 12. Qxd4.} 
10. Qxd3
10. Nd7 {Threatening ...Nxe5 followed by ...Qxd3 when the endgame is already favorable for Black. White now has a choice between different ways of supporting the e5-knight. The main move by far is 11. f4.} 
11. f4 {This is what White usually plays. He wants to keep the knight on e5, and in case Black plays ...Nxe5, not have to recapture with the d4-pawn (which would allow Black to exchange queens on d3 and get a very nice endgame).Here, too, White has some alternatives in11.Bf4and11.Qe2.} 
11. Be7 {This move, followed by the pawn grab12.Bd2Bxh4!,is what revitalized the entire 7...e6 line. For example, if we take GM Negi's 2014 1. e4 repertoire (the last big White repertoire that I'm aware of that recommended the classical 3. Nc3 variation), he doesn't even take 11...Be7 seriously. His only comment is 'The greedy12...Bxh4?!13.O-O-Ogives White a huge lead in development and is much too risky for Black'.Since the year 2016 12...Bxh4 is being played a lot, though, as players have discovered that Black is completely fine.} 
12. Bd2 {The main continuation. White ignores the threat to his h4-pawn and prepares to castle long.Here an important alternative is12.Nh5!?Ngf6!13.Nxg7+Kf814.Nxe6+fxe6when White has sacrificed a piece for two pawns and a long-term initiative. The arising positions are hard to play for both sides and approximately equal with best play.} 
12. Nxe5 {First we eliminate the knight, then we take the h4-pawn.12...Bxh4?would be the wrong move order because after13.Nxd7we would have to retake with the king on d7.} 
13. fxe5
13. Bxh4
14. O-O-O {After any other move we would also play ...Bxg3 followed by ...Ne7.} 
14. Bxg3
15. Qxg3
15. Ne7 {This is the starting position of the mainline of 7... e6. White will usually grab on g7 next, while Black activates his forces with ...Qd5, ...Rg8 and ...Nf5. With correct play the game should simplify into a more or less equal endgame of queen (Black) vs two rooks (White).} 
