7. Nd7 {Here we can't - and don't need to - safeguard the g6-bishop, and we can immediately attack/ question the e5-knight instead.} 
8. Nxg6
8. hxg6 {This kind of pawn structure should be familiar to seasoned Caro-Kann players. Here it is important to note that the g3-knight is misplaced, as the g6-pawn takes away important squares. The half-open h-file also comes in handy. White has the bishop pair, but Black's smooth development more than compensates for that.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Classical Variation: 4...Bf5 With 7...e6"]
[Black "Classical 7...e6: 8.h5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {3.Nd2dxe4amounts to the same thing. This is the so-called 'Classical' Caro-Kann, which was very popular from the mid-20th century up until the early 2010s, but it has fallen out of fashion nowadays. Still, there is nothing wrong at all with White's setup.} 
3. dxe4
4. Nxe4
4. Bf5 {Here the mainline of4...Nf65.Nxf6exf6seems to have defanged the 3.Nc3/3.Nd2 variation. It continues6.c3Bd67.Bd3O-O8.Qc2Re8+9.Ne2and now9...h5!equalizes for Black. This 4...Nf6 line is analyzed in some detail in both LTR: Caro-Kann and Keep It Simple for Black.The more traditional mainline of4...Bf5holds up well too, but it's a lot more lines to memorize and in some variations White gets a hair-raising attack and Black has to find some complicated defensive maneuvers, after which the game usually ends in some perpetual or repetition of moves. I want to suggest a sideline of 4...Bf5, however, which significantly cuts down on the theory.} 
5. Ng3
5. Bg6
6. h4 {White also has some other tries, usually involving a setup with6.Bc4and/or developing the g1-knight to f4 via e2 or h3, which I am not going to analyze here.} 
6. h6
7. Nf3 {Here the traditional mainline continues with7...Nd7,as White is 'threatening' to move the f3-knight to the e5-square, gaining a tempo on the bishop on g6 in the process (as, after playing ...h6, Black definitely doesn't want to allow Nxg6 fxg6 wrecking his pawn structure).However, there are two interesting sidelines here in7...Nf6and7...e6with which Black allows White to carry out this 'threat'.} 
7. e6 {Allowing White to play Ne5. The counterargument to the main move 7...Nd7 is that the b8-knight is not ideal on d7 - it would be better if Black could play ...c5 and then ...Nc6. By first playing ...e6 and delaying the development of the b8-knight, we keep open that possibility.Secondly, if White moves the knight to e5 early on, it can become a target there. Finally, of course,7...e6contains a lot less theory than the mainline7...Nd78.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3etc. Not to mention that your opponent will be less likely to know what to do against it.} 
8. h5 {White plays as if Black put the knight on d7 instead of moving e7-e6. I was surprised to learn that in online games this is White's most popular move, as it's definitely not the most principled.} 
8. Bh7
9. Bd3
9. Bxd3
10. Qxd3
10. Nf6 {The knight will have to go here anyway, so we might as well develop it right away. Now White almost always develops the c1-bishop to either d2 or f4, just as in the 7... Nd7 mainline. At that point, Black can transpose to said mainline with 11...Nbd7, but that would be rather accomodating. We can play in different ways.} 
11. Bf4 {11.Be3likely transposes after11...Qa5+12.Bd2.} 
11. Qa5+ {At first I was mainly looking into11...c5,as the option of moving the b8-knight to c6 is one of the things that makes the 7...e6 different from the mainline 7... Nd7. However, that's not the only difference.Against 11.Bf4 in the mainline, the move 11...Qa5+ is the main antidote. In that position Black has the b8-knight on d7 while the f6-knight is yet on g8. As a result, White gets some extra ideas involving Ne4-d6+, for example after12.Bd2Bb4there is13.Ne4!?, or after13.c3Be714.c4Black is advised to retreat the queen with14...Qc7, as14...Bb4?!15.Ne4!is a better version of 13. Ne4 for White.However, currently we have our knight on f6 already, which means that White cannot pose any threats with Ne4 whatsoever - we'd just chop that knight off!} 
12. c3 {This is an interesting sideline that deserves attention. However, it's rather committal on White's part. The point is that White intends to advance the queenside pawns (starting with a2-a4, then b2-b4, etc.). This means he'll likely castle kingside, but with the h-pawn already on h5 that does pose some risks for him.} 
12. Nbd7 {Just developing. After the immediate12...Nd5,13.Be5can be annoying.} 
13. a4 {That's usually how White plays. There have also been some games with13.Ne5, but just13...Be7and 14...O-O seems perfectly fine for Black.} 
13. c5 {This is my suggestion. Instead, the main move is13...Nd5, but I think that after14.Bd2Qc715.a5Black is getting pushed around a bit too much and losing a lot of space.} 
14. O-O {14.dxc5Nxc515.Qc4Qa6!seems to equalize. In many of these endgames the h5-pawn sticks out like a sore thumb - White can almost never move the g3-knight away without dropping this pawn.} 
14. Be7 {Just finishing development.} 
15. Rfe1 {At this point we need to pay attention. White intends15...O-O16.Nf5!.} 
15. Qd8 {I think this is the easiest solution. The computer thinks15...O-O16.Nf5Bd8!?is defensible, but I would rather avoid this possibility.} 
16. Qe2 {Renewing the pin on the e-file, but I don't think we have to be worried anymore here.} 
16. O-O {Now after17.Nf5the e7-bishop is not actually hanging, so we could just grab the h5-pawn in return, but also17...Re8is perfectly fine. In the same line with the immediate15...O-O,16.Nf5Rfe8?is not a good idea because of17.Rxe6!fxe618.Nxh6+!gxh619.Qg6+with a winning attack. A very typical pattern for such positions.} 
