11. c5 {Now White usually plays either12.O-O-Oor12.Ne4. A few minor alternatives:A)12.Qb5+?!Qd713.Qxd7+Nbxd7and White has to struggle for equality in the endgame.B) There is also12.Bc3, but after12...Nc6White likely transposes back to 12.O-O-O by playing13.O-O-O.} 
12. Ne4 {This is the 2nd most popular move in my database, but it's definitely White's best try for an advantage. There is immediate pressure on Black's position while Black has yet to develop most of their pieces.} 
12. Nc6 {Black needs to keep developing. All the alternatives just suck.} 
13. Bc3 {The bishop is well-placed here.13.Be3is less active, and also allows13...Qa5+14.c3Rd8!.} 
13. cxd4 {All the alternatives simply look worse, as White was now intending to play 14. dxc5 if allowed. For instance,13...Nd514.dxc5!Nxc315.Qxc3Qd516.Nd6+!and Black does not get the pawn back, as g7 is hanging after Black takes twice on d6.} 
14. Nxd4
14. Nb4 {The only alternative is14...Nxd4, but that immediately leads to an endgame where White is playing for two results:15.Nxf6+Qxf616.Qxd4Qxd417.Bxd4and White is better, even if it's not much.With14...Nb4we avoid our pawn structure being compromised by White taking Nxc6, we threaten the queen (and the c2-pawn in some circumstances) and we can reroute the knight to d5 if necessary.Now White usually gives a check on b5 with the queen or takes on f6, and they can transpose.} 
15. Nxf6+ {15.Qb5+Qd7and now White usually takes16.Nxf6+which transposes back to 15. Nxf6+.} 
15. gxf6
16. Qb5+ {This forces the exchange of queens.} 
16. Qd7
17. Qxd7+
17. Kxd7 {White has some pressure in this ending, not because of Black's compromised kingside pawn structure - which is actually quite useful - but because our king is a bit awkward at the moment, especially if White immediately occupies the d-file.} 
18. Rd1 {This is hard to meet. Try to find a square for the king where it doesn't hamper Black's piece coordination or allows a knight check followed by Bxf6!} 
18. Nd5 {In fact18...Rg8seems fine too, but after White moves the d4-knight Black will have to play 19...Nd5 anyway.} 
19. Bd2 {The threat is c2-c4.} 
19. Rc8 {With very accurate play White can keep some edge here. That being said, for now Black has defended against all threats, and if White continues quietly then the tables could turn quite quickly, e.g. with ...Bc5 or ...Rg8-g4.This seems like White's best try after 8. h5. As this is a rare system for Black, I doubt you'll ever see it over the board. But it pays to be aware of your opponent's best options.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Classical Variation: 4...Bf5 With 7...e6"]
[Black "Classical 7...e6: 8.Bd3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {3.Nd2dxe4amounts to the same thing. This is the so-called 'Classical' Caro-Kann, which was very popular from the mid-20th century up until the early 2010s, but it has fallen out of fashion nowadays. Still, there is nothing wrong at all with White's setup.} 
3. dxe4
4. Nxe4
4. Bf5 {Here the mainline of4...Nf65.Nxf6exf6seems to have defanged the 3.Nc3/3.Nd2 variation. It continues6.c3Bd67.Bd3O-O8.Qc2Re8+9.Ne2and now9...h5!equalizes for Black. This 4...Nf6 line is analyzed in some detail in both LTR: Caro-Kann and Keep It Simple for Black.The more traditional mainline of4...Bf5holds up well too, but it's a lot more lines to memorize and in some variations White gets a hair-raising attack and Black has to find some complicated defensive maneuvers, after which the game usually ends in some perpetual or repetition of moves. I want to suggest a sideline of 4...Bf5, however, which significantly cuts down on the theory.} 
5. Ng3
5. Bg6
6. h4 {White also has some other tries, usually involving a setup with6.Bc4and/or developing the g1-knight to f4 via e2 or h3, which I am not going to analyze here.} 
6. h6
7. Nf3 {Here the traditional mainline continues with7...Nd7,as White is 'threatening' to move the f3-knight to the e5-square, gaining a tempo on the bishop on g6 in the process (as, after playing ...h6, Black definitely doesn't want to allow Nxg6 fxg6 wrecking his pawn structure).However, there are two interesting sidelines here in7...Nf6and7...e6with which Black allows White to carry out this 'threat'.} 
7. e6 {Allowing White to play Ne5. The counterargument to the main move 7...Nd7 is that the b8-knight is not ideal on d7 - it would be better if Black could play ...c5 and then ...Nc6. By first playing ...e6 and delaying the development of the b8-knight, we keep open that possibility.Secondly, if White moves the knight to e5 early on, it can become a target there. Finally, of course,7...e6contains a lot less theory than the mainline7...Nd78.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3etc. Not to mention that your opponent will be less likely to know what to do against it.} 
8. Bd3 {Exchanging the bishops without pushing h4-h5 is also possible. Sometimes the difference without including the move h4-h5 is negligible, sometimes it actually matters. I'll only show a few lines where it makes a difference.} 
8. Bxd3
9. Qxd3
9. Nf6
10. O-O {This is played quiet often on Lichess.} 
10. Bd6 {We don't necessarily intend to double White's pawns on g3, but a lot of players feel uncomfortable at the possibility.} 
11. Ne4
11. Nxe4
12. Qxe4
12. O-O {A typical Caro-Kann position, but White's h-pawn seems misplaced whenever White castles short in such positions.} 
