5. Ng3
5. Bg6
6. h4 {White also has some other tries, usually involving a setup with6.Bc4and/or developing the g1-knight to f4 via e2 or h3, which I am not going to analyze here.} 
6. h6
7. Nf3 {Here the traditional mainline continues with7...Nd7,as White is 'threatening' to move the f3-knight to the e5-square, gaining a tempo on the bishop on g6 in the process (as, after playing ...h6, Black definitely doesn't want to allow Nxg6 fxg6 wrecking his pawn structure).However, there are two interesting sidelines here in7...Nf6and7...e6with which Black allows White to carry out this 'threat'.} 
7. e6 {Allowing White to play Ne5. The counterargument to the main move 7...Nd7 is that the b8-knight is not ideal on d7 - it would be better if Black could play ...c5 and then ...Nc6. By first playing ...e6 and delaying the development of the b8-knight, we keep open that possibility.Secondly, if White moves the knight to e5 early on, it can become a target there. Finally, of course,7...e6contains a lot less theory than the mainline7...Nd78.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3etc. Not to mention that your opponent will be less likely to know what to do against it.} 
8. Ne5 {The most-played move and White's principled attempt to punish Black for 'forgetting' to play ...Nd7.} 
8. Bh7
9. Bd3 {After pushing our light-squared bishop around, White exchanges it, just as in the old mainline of 4... Bf5.} 
9. Bxd3 {Taking the d4-pawn is not just dubious, but loses immediately to a tactic worth knowing:9...Qxd4?10.Nxf7!Kxf711.Bg6+and 12. Qxd4.} 
10. Qxd3
10. Nd7 {Threatening ...Nxe5 followed by ...Qxd3 when the endgame is already favorable for Black. White now has a choice between different ways of supporting the e5-knight. The main move by far is 11. f4.} 
11. Bf4 {The 2nd most played move after11.f4, but this feels a bit insipid.} 
11. Nxe5
12. Bxe5 {The bishop is quite well-positioned on e5, but now we can make use of its absence on the queenside.} 
12. Qa5+ {We give a check while White can't interpose his dark-squared bishop, and this way make it difficult for White to castle long since the a2-pawn would remain hanging.} 
13. c3
13. Nf6 {We develop the knight first as we don't want to allow13...Be7?14.Bxg7.} 
14. Bxf6 {This seems to be fairly common online, so let's see how Black deals with this.} 
14. gxf6
15. Ne4
15. Be7
16. Qf3 {White keeps making one move threats, but they can all easily be answered.} 
16. f5 {Meanwhile, these moves don't improve White's position, while Black is developing and improving his pawn structure.} 
17. Nd2
17. Rg8 {Next we can consider ...Qd5. If White exchanges queens on d5, we retake with the c6-pawn and can play for a minority attack on the queenside.} 
