11. Ngf6
12. Bd2
12. c5 {I think we should make use of White's early Qe2 move by undermining the d4-pawn at an equally early stage.} 
13. Nxd7
13. Qxd7
14. dxc5 {White is opening up the position, counting on their slightly superior development.} 
14. Bxc5
15. O-O-O
15. Qc6 {The queen is nicely positioned here, controlling the e4-square, attacking g2, eyeing White's king on the c-file.15...Qa4is an interesting alternative though.} 
16. Bc3 {This looks like the only challenging move. After other moves Black just castles or plays ...Rc8.} 
16. Be7 {We should not allow doubled f-pawns for now.} 
17. Nh5 {17.Bxf6Bxf618.Nh5Ke7!19.Nxf6gxf6and Black's king is perfectly safe in the center.} 
17. Nxh5
18. Qxh5
18. Rc8 {Keeping White's bishop pinned.} 
19. Rh3
19. Qc4 {19...Bf6?!20.Qe2!is less accurate, when White is threatening Bxf6 followed by Rc3.After19...Qc4it seems like Black can keep equality with correct play, although the position is quite rich. ... Rc5 is a resource, while if20.Rd4Black can repeat moves with20...Qf1+21.Rd1Qc4.} 
