10. Nd7 {Threatening ...Nxe5 followed by ...Qxd3 when the endgame is already favorable for Black. White now has a choice between different ways of supporting the e5-knight. The main move by far is 11. f4.} 
11. f4 {This is what White usually plays. He wants to keep the knight on e5, and in case Black plays ...Nxe5, not have to recapture with the d4-pawn (which would allow Black to exchange queens on d3 and get a very nice endgame).} 
11. Be7 {This move, followed by the pawn grab12.Bd2Bxh4!,is what revitalized the entire 7...e6 line. For example, if we take GM Negi's 2014 1.e4 repertoire (the last big White repertoire that I'm aware of that recommended the classical 3.Nc3 variation), he doesn't even take 11... Be7 seriously. His only comment is 'The greedy12...Bxh4?!13.O-O-Ogives White a huge lead in development and is much too risky for Black'.Since the year 201612...Bxh4is being played a lot, though, as players have discovered that Black is completely fine.} 
12. Bd2 {The main continuation. White ignores the threat to his h4-pawn and prepares to castle long.} 
12. Nxe5 {First we eliminate the knight, then we take the h4-pawn.12...Bxh4?would be the wrong move order because after13.Nxd7we would have to retake with the king on d7.} 
13. fxe5
13. Bxh4
14. O-O-O {After any other move we would also play ...Bxg3 followed by ...Ne7.} 
14. Bxg3
15. Qxg3
15. Ne7 {The point is to give back the pawn on g7 and then activate the queen via d5. The rook will go to g8, while the knight typically ends up on f5.15...g5?16.Bxg5and15...g6?!16.Kb1are both not recommendable for Black, the former just losing while the latter gives White too much play on the dark squares.Now after15...Ne7the main move by far is the straightforward16.Qxg7, but there are a few minor alternatives to consider first:16.Bb4and16.Qf2.} 
16. Bb4 {A logical move, but it doesn't promise White full compensation.} 
16. Nf5 {Now after most queen moves, ...Qg5+ usually gives Black very good play.} 
17. Qb3 {White is intending to sacrifice another pawn with d4-d5 with complications. For instance,17...Qg5+18.Kb1Qxg219.d5!.} 
17. h5 {17...Qd5is a solid alternative, as Black is always at least slightly better after the exchange of queens, while18.c4Qxg2is dubious for White.} 
18. g4 {18.d5probably has to be tried, although I don't see how White is making progress after18...exd5. Here too19.g4is answered by19...Qg5+.} 
18. Qg5+ {That's the idea. After19.Kb1Qxg4we grab another pawn.} 
