7. e6 {Allowing White to play Ne5. The counterargument to the main move 7...Nd7 is that the b8-knight is not ideal on d7 - it would be better if Black could play ...c5 and then ...Nc6. By first playing ...e6 and delaying the development of the b8-knight, we keep open that possibility.Secondly, if White moves the knight to e5 early on, it can become a target there. Finally, of course,7...e6contains a lot less theory than the mainline7...Nd78.h5Bh79.Bd3Bxd310.Qxd3etc. Not to mention that your opponent will be less likely to know what to do against it.} 
8. Ne5 {The most-played move and White's principled attempt to punish Black for 'forgetting' to play ...Nd7.} 
8. Bh7
9. Bd3 {After pushing our light-squared bishop around, White exchanges it, just as in the old mainline of 4... Bf5.} 
9. Bxd3 {Taking the d4-pawn is not just dubious, but loses immediately to a tactic worth knowing:9...Qxd4?10.Nxf7!Kxf711.Bg6+and 12. Qxd4.} 
10. Qxd3
10. Nd7 {Threatening ...Nxe5 followed by ...Qxd3 when the endgame is already favorable for Black. White now has a choice between different ways of supporting the e5-knight. The main move by far is 11. f4.} 
11. f4 {This is what White usually plays. He wants to keep the knight on e5, and in case Black plays ...Nxe5, not have to recapture with the d4-pawn (which would allow Black to exchange queens on d3 and get a very nice endgame).} 
11. Be7 {This move, followed by the pawn grab12.Bd2Bxh4!,is what revitalized the entire 7...e6 line. For example, if we take GM Negi's 2014 1.e4 repertoire (the last big White repertoire that I'm aware of that recommended the classical 3.Nc3 variation), he doesn't even take 11... Be7 seriously. His only comment is 'The greedy12...Bxh4?!13.O-O-Ogives White a huge lead in development and is much too risky for Black'.Since the year 201612...Bxh4is being played a lot, though, as players have discovered that Black is completely fine.} 
12. Bd2 {The main continuation. White ignores the threat to his h4-pawn and prepares to castle long.} 
12. Nxe5 {First we eliminate the knight, then we take the h4-pawn.12...Bxh4?would be the wrong move order because after13.Nxd7we would have to retake with the king on d7.} 
13. fxe5
13. Bxh4
14. O-O-O {After any other move we would also play ...Bxg3 followed by ...Ne7.} 
14. Bxg3
15. Qxg3
15. Ne7 {The point is to give back the pawn on g7 and then activate the queen via d5. The rook will go to g8, while the knight typically ends up on f5.15...g5?16.Bxg5and15...g6?!16.Kb1are both not recommendable for Black, the former just losing while the latter gives White too much play on the dark squares.Now after15...Ne7the main move by far is the straightforward16.Qxg7, but there are a few minor alternatives to consider first:16.Bb4and16.Qf2.} 
16. Qxg7 {Taking on g7 is almost universally played.} 
16. Rg8 {Not much choice for Black there! The rook was attacked and we defend it with a counterattack. Now White actually has a choice between three moves:17.Qxh6(the main move and the most obvious),17.Qh7and17.Qf6.} 
17. Qxh6
17. Qd5 {Now White should probably take the time to guard the a2-pawn with18.Kb1,which is indeed the most common move, but occasionally White deviates - in which case we should pretty much always take the a2-pawn.} 
18. Bg5 {This might look like it makes life difficult for Black, but in fact it's White's king who is in more trouble.} 
18. Qxa2
19. c3 {19.Qf6Nd5doesn't help White.} 
19. Kd7 {Since castling is out of the question, we activate our queenside rook in this alternative way.} 
20. Bxe7 {A more controlled way of playing is20.Qf6Rae821.Rh7, when Black can choose between21...Qa1+22.Kc2Qa4+and White would have to chance moving their king to d2 to keep the game going, or21...Kc822.Qxf7Rgf8with a very double-edged game.} 
20. Rxg2 {I feel like this is the easiest way to secure the draw, though there are alternatives to be considered. Probably the most natural is20...Rg6intending21.Qh3Kxe7with good play, but21.Qxg6!fxg622.Bd6looks quite dangerous for Black.Definitely avoid20...Kxe7??21.Qf6+Ke822.Rh8though, when White will win the rook on a8.} 
21. Rd2 {The only move.} 
21. Qa1+
22. Kc2
22. Rxd2+
23. Kxd2
23. Qxb2+
24. Kd3
24. Rg8 {Capturing the bishop is still not possible, but White's king is very open now and we can keep his pieces tied up.} 
25. Bg5 {Only move.} 
25. c5 {Threatening26.--c4+when27.Kxc4runs into27...Rc8+.It's very likely that the c3-pawn will fall and/or some kind of perpetual soon arises. For instance, one of Stockfish's mainlines runs26.Rc1Qg2!27.Qf627.Be3c4+!28.Kxc4Qe2+29.Kb3Rg2and White has to give up the bishop by putting it on d227...Qxg528.Qxf7+Kd829.Qxb7Qxc1etc.} 
