18. O-O-O
19. Qf6 {Attacking the knight on e7, the pawn on f7 and preparing Rh7.} 
19. Rxg2 {This is my recommendation, but I will add that the move19...Nf5is also very playable - it's a matter of taste as to what type of endgame you'd prefer to play.19...Rxg2seems to lead to an ending where Black has a queen against two rooks, whereas19...Nf5leads to an ending of rook+knight vs rook+bishop with an extra pawn for White, but where it seems nearly impossible for him to make progress.Judge for yourself:19...Nf520.Rh7Qxd421.Qxf7Qd722.Qxd7+Rxd723.Rxd7Kxd724.Bf4+Kc725.g3and this is close to equal according to Stockfish. Personally I would rather play the queen vs 2 rooks ending, though.} 
20. Qxe7
20. Rxd2 {That's why Black is not losing a piece.} 
21. Qxd8+ {This is how White should keep the game going.} 
21. Kxd8
22. Rh8+ {Next White can recapture the rook on d2, reaching an ending of two rooks vs a queen.} 
22. Ke7
23. Rxd2
23. Qe4 {Most games instead continued23...c524.c3Qe4+25.Kc1cxd4etc.,but why not switch the move order? After 23... Qe4 first, White has to respond to the threat of ...Qe1+, and then ...c5 undermines the d4- and e5-pawns while White is not able to play c2-c3 any longer.--- There are more ways of playing this position, which you can check out with an engine. For instance, one of the '0.00' lines is23...c524.c3b5!?followed by ...a5 and ...b4, just throwing all the queenside pawns forward. More often than not, though, it seems like Black has to force a perpetual check there.} 
24. Rd1
24. c5 {That's the idea, now that White can't play c2-c3.} 
25. dxc5
25. Qxe5
26. Rhd8
26. f5 {We start to get our pawns rolling and create a nice square on f6 for our king. I think there are three results possible in this ending, though objectively it's of course equal.} 
