[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Addendum: Various Early Ne5 Moves"]
[Black "4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 - The antidote: 5... Qa5+!"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Nf3 {This is actually not an innocuous move order either.} 
4. Nc6
5. Bb5 {This is one of the move orders that Gawain covers although there is a small omission on his part. It's also not covered in Keep it Simple for Black (which is fair enough, as it is a strange sideline and you can only mention so much).} 
5. Qa5+ {This is Erwin L'Ami's recommendation and I think it is clearly best. The point is that White's queenside is forced to position awkwardly.} 
6. Nc3
6. Bg4
7. h3 {Another line is7.Bd2when it's important to insert7...Rc8!, so that8.Nxd5can be answered with8...Qxb5without having to worry about a knight fork on c7.} 
7. Bxf3
8. Qxf3
8. e6 {The line continues on for some number of moves and I'll refer you to Erwin's course for the details, but the issue really is that White's queenside pieces are tangled. Ideally White wants to 1) keep the bishop pair, 2) get a pawn chain with b2-c3-d4. Here it's very difficult to achieve both. The c3-knight obviously can't move without dropping the bishop on b5. But if the b5-bishop moves, the c6-knight is no longer pinned and White has to reckon with both ... Nxd4 and ...Nb4.} 
