[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Addendum: Various Early Ne5 Moves"]
[Black "4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3!?"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Nf3 {This is actually not an innocuous move order either.} 
4. Nc6
5. c3 {I should add this curious sideline, as it has been used against me in the past. Objectively it's nothing special but there are some tricks to be aware of...} 
5. Bg4 {Naturally.} 
6. Qb3 {This is White's idea. Now6...Bxf3?!is not that good because White can play7.Qxb7!in-between. Black might be able to limit the damage in the ending after7...Qc88.Qxc8+Rxc89.gxf3Nxd4, but still it's White who is pushing there.} 
6. Qd7 {As 6... Bxf3 doesn't work that well, this is the main move.} 
7. Ne5 {White's idea.} 
7. Nxe5 {Not much choice there.} 
8. dxe5
8. a6 {Again not much choice; we had to defend against the threat of Bb5.} 
9. Na3 {This looks weird, but there is again a tactical point: White would like to continue with Nb5! when the knight is immune, and then perhaps a4-a5 and Be3 with some bind on the queenside.It all looks very obscure, but it has been played before and can be really annoying if you have to face without knowing what is going on!} 
9. Rc8 {I think this is the best way, simply stopping Nb5 in its tracks.} 
10. Nb5
10. axb5 {Now this works out for Black.} 
11. Bxb5
11. Rc6
12. a4
12. Qc7 {We need to be quick and immediately address the pin on the rook, as otherwise a5-a6 can become very awkward.} 
13. a5
13. Bd7
14. Bxc6
14. Qxc6 {Black has a material advantage and a5-a6 is no longer a thing.} 
