[Black "4. Ne5 Nc6 5. f4?"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Ne5 {The idea is to frustrate Black's development and force us to give up the bishop pair, as we will see.} 
4. Nc6
5. f4 {While preparing for a match in the Dutch league, I discovered that one of my potential opponents had played this dubious move in hundreds (!) of bullet and blitz games online, and had a pretty decent score with it. However, strictly speaking it is just an inferior version of the line5.d4.} 
5. Bf5 {The main thing to keep in mind about such positions is that Black almost never wants to exchange on e5, which transforms the pawn structure in White's favor and makes it nearly impossible to get the c8-bishop out. We do want to get rid of the knight on e5, but we should do this by forcing White to either retreat it or exchange it on c6.One difference with 5. d4 is that the developing move 5... Bf5! is available, as White no longer has good means to harass this bishop - the f4-pawn is a convenient shield and, if necessary, the e4-square is always available! Next we intend to develop in the exact same way as after 5. d4 - ...e6, ...Bd6, ...Nge7, ...O-O and eventually ...f6.} 
6. d4
6. e6 {Black will be slightly better with natural moves and the above-mentioned plan. White has weakened their light squares by prematurely playing f2-f4.} 
