[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Addendum: Various Early Ne5 Moves"]
[Black "4. Ne5 Nc6 5. Bb5 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Ne5 {The idea is to frustrate Black's development and force us to give up the bishop pair, as we will see.} 
4. Nc6
5. d4 {The main move order, though Black does get an extra option which is utilized by Erwin L'Ami:5...a6is what he recommends and is not bad either. If you don't like the positions after5...e6(they are objectively fine though, and not very hard to learn) then this is a worthwhile alternative to look into... though you had better also look into what Gawain recommends against5...a6.} 
5. e6 {We have to block in the c8-bishop, but it will be fine.5...Bf5?!6.Bb5Rc87.O-Owill see the f5-bishop soon be subject to a pawn storm with g4 and h4.The thing to keep in mind about the position after 5... e6 is that White has already wasted some time, moving the kingside knight twice, and it can soon be put under more pressure with ...Bd6, ...Qc7 (or if he waits too long, we castle and play ...f6). He really needs to be able to show something concrete for this quickly, otherwise White's strategy has just failed. I should mention in this regard that Stockfish thinks that in the position after 5... e6, White's second best move behind 6. Bb5 is actually the retreat 6. Nf3, which can't be what White had in mind when playing this!} 
6. Bb5 {The only move with which White can hope for some advantage.} 
6. Bd7 {Other moves allow White to get some initiative with c2-c4 or something else. Here we threaten7.--Nxe5with a rubber band trick (8.Bxd7+Nxd7) and there is only one good move for White.} 
7. Nxd7 {White gets the bishop pair as something tangible, but Black has no weaknesses and smooth development.} 
7. Qxd7
8. c3
8. Bd6
9. O-O
9. Nf6 {In these positions we need to keep the idea of putting the knight on e4 in mind, as sometimes White will allow this.} 
10. Nd2 {First10.Re1is also possible, it should amount to the same thing.} 
10. O-O {Keep it Simple for Black continues with10...Qc7, but let's follow Gawain's mainline here.} 
11. Re1 {11.Nf3would allow a setup with11...Ne4!, which Gawain would like to prevent.} 
11. Rae8 {Gawain thinks this rare move is critical. Black continues to eye the idea ...e5, while not yet playing it.} 
12. Bd3
12. e5 {is already very good for Black, as Gawain mentions. Black gains a further tempo on White's bishop after the exchange on e5.} 
13. dxe5
13. Nxe5 {Black has a serious initiative. A sample line is14.Be2Neg415.Bxg4Nxg416.Nf1Qc717.g3Rxe118.Qxe1Bc519.Be3Nxe320.Nxe3Re8and White is forced to accept an ugly weakness on e3.} 
